1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:04,136
[SPEAKER_21]: First, a Change the Build schedule, a Leader's Special of Question Time.

2
00:00:04,337 --> 00:00:11,325
[SPEAKER_21]: You can go online to BBC News to follow all the analysis with the BBC's Reality Check from the comfort of your own couch.

3
00:00:16,092 --> 00:00:17,754
[SPEAKER_44]: Tonight, we're in Sheffield.

4
00:00:17,814 --> 00:00:21,178
[SPEAKER_44]: Welcome to Question Time, Election Leaders Special.

5
00:00:30,237 --> 00:00:37,905
[SPEAKER_44]: For the first time, all four leaders of the UK's main political parties will answer questions one after the other from a Question Time audience.

6
00:00:39,006 --> 00:00:40,107
[SPEAKER_44]: This one right here.

7
00:00:40,447 --> 00:00:46,833
[SPEAKER_44]: Everyone gets the same amount of time, just under half an hour, to respond to what our audience wants to ask about their policies.

8
00:00:47,234 --> 00:00:49,476
[SPEAKER_44]: We'll begin with the Labour leader, Jeremy Corbyn.

9
00:00:49,636 --> 00:00:59,586
[SPEAKER_44]: Then at 7.30, the First Minister of Scotland and leader of the Scottish National Party, Nicola Sturgeon, followed by the leader of the Liberal Democrats, Joe Swinson, at 8 o'clock.

10
00:00:59,566 --> 00:01:04,037
[SPEAKER_44]: And finally, at 8.30, the Conservative leader and Prime Minister, Boris Johnson.

11
00:01:04,538 --> 00:01:09,490
[SPEAKER_44]: And remember, as always, you can join in on Twitter, on Facebook, on Instagram, in the usual way.

12
00:01:10,392 --> 00:01:12,116
[SPEAKER_44]: So, let's get started.

13
00:01:12,237 --> 00:01:17,389
[SPEAKER_44]: Without further ado, will you please join me in welcoming the leader of the Labour Party, Jeremy Corbyn.

14
00:01:37,028 --> 00:01:37,909
[SPEAKER_44]: Good evening, Mr Corbyn.

15
00:01:37,929 --> 00:01:39,512
[SPEAKER_44]: Thank you very much for being with us.

16
00:01:39,752 --> 00:01:40,213
[SPEAKER_44]: It's a pleasure.

17
00:01:40,433 --> 00:01:48,125
[SPEAKER_44]: Before we start, and I promise you I'm saying this to everybody, the aim tonight is to allow our audience here to ask you as many questions as possible.

18
00:01:48,145 --> 00:01:51,650
[SPEAKER_44]: So if you could keep your answers brief and to the point, that would be great.

19
00:01:51,730 --> 00:01:54,434
[SPEAKER_44]: And I hope you'll forgive me for interrupting if you don't.

20
00:01:54,955 --> 00:01:58,721
[SPEAKER_44]: So let's have our first question from Ian Parkin.

21
00:02:00,764 --> 00:02:01,565
[SPEAKER_09]: Good evening, Jeremy.

22
00:02:02,206 --> 00:02:05,972
[SPEAKER_09]: Should businesses be frightened of an incoming Labour government?

23
00:02:06,323 --> 00:02:21,871
[SPEAKER_07]: No, they should not be frightened of an incoming Labour government because our country's economy relies on many small and medium-sized enterprises that are the motor of our economy that often have great difficulty in accessing capital and accessing support for what they're trying to do.

24
00:02:22,372 --> 00:02:28,062
[SPEAKER_07]: The biggest businesses will be asked to pay a little bit more in corporation tax, but it will be lower

25
00:02:28,042 --> 00:02:32,967
[SPEAKER_07]: than it was in 2010, and indeed lower than the average for most industrial countries.

26
00:02:33,207 --> 00:02:37,973
[SPEAKER_07]: What I want to do is ensure that there is an economy thriving in every part of the country.

27
00:02:38,233 --> 00:02:39,895
[SPEAKER_07]: And so that means the resources.

28
00:02:40,195 --> 00:02:43,719
[SPEAKER_07]: It means an infrastructure system, roads and railways all across the country.

29
00:02:43,839 --> 00:02:48,704
[SPEAKER_07]: It means broadband in every part of our country that's free to everyone to use.

30
00:02:48,904 --> 00:02:52,208
[SPEAKER_07]: And that will mean that businesses can be set up anywhere.

31
00:02:52,228 --> 00:02:53,509
[SPEAKER_07]: It also

32
00:02:53,489 --> 00:03:08,647
[SPEAKER_07]: It is also clear in our manifesto here that what we're keen to do is ensure there is a better trained workforce in our society, so we will be promoting apprenticeships and skilled training at every level and give them the same value as academic education in universities.

33
00:03:08,667 --> 00:03:18,579
[SPEAKER_07]: And so I enjoy working with all the business organisations, setting out clearly our views on public ownership, our views on taxation and our views on investment for the future.

34
00:03:18,839 --> 00:03:20,461
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, there's two people with their hands up.

35
00:03:20,481 --> 00:03:20,982
[SPEAKER_44]: Let's hear from you both.

36
00:03:22,632 --> 00:03:25,296
[SPEAKER_44]: Starting with you, sir.

37
00:03:25,316 --> 00:03:28,982
[SPEAKER_18]: To be honest, Mr Corbyn, I don't think it's businesses who should be scared just.

38
00:03:29,022 --> 00:03:30,024
[SPEAKER_18]: I think it's everyone.

39
00:03:30,485 --> 00:03:41,122
[SPEAKER_18]: Your reckless socialist ideas are genuinely terrifying to me, my family and my friends, and I think freedom will completely erode if we let you have the keys to number 10.

40
00:03:41,583 --> 00:03:44,387
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, before you answer, Mr Corbyn, can I hear from you as well, please?

41
00:03:44,536 --> 00:03:48,230
[SPEAKER_19]: So what about the businesses that you're going to nationalise that then won't exist?

42
00:03:48,591 --> 00:03:53,128
[SPEAKER_19]: So when you're saying about free internet and the other likes of Virgin and Sky, then they haven't got a product to sell.

43
00:03:54,982 --> 00:04:03,854
[SPEAKER_07]: The issue of your views on rights and freedoms in our society, I absolutely defend the right of free speech.

44
00:04:04,675 --> 00:04:06,999
[SPEAKER_07]: I supported the introduction of the Human Rights Act.

45
00:04:07,059 --> 00:04:09,182
[SPEAKER_07]: I support the Convention on Human Rights.

46
00:04:09,282 --> 00:04:12,947
[SPEAKER_07]: Freedoms and rights in a democracy are very, very important.

47
00:04:13,247 --> 00:04:19,796
[SPEAKER_07]: I spent my life getting into hot water for defending people because I believe their human rights should not be violated.

48
00:04:19,836 --> 00:04:23,942
[SPEAKER_07]: And that's the kind of government that I intend to lead that does guarantee democracy.

49
00:04:23,922 --> 00:04:26,209
[SPEAKER_44]: So why do you think this man is frightened of you being in power?

50
00:04:27,352 --> 00:04:34,973
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, I can't understand what everything is going on in your mind that makes you say that, but whatever.

51
00:04:34,994 --> 00:04:39,045
[SPEAKER_07]: Maybe we can talk about it later if you like.

52
00:04:40,156 --> 00:04:56,883
[SPEAKER_07]: I want to live in a society where we do deal with the worst aspects of poverty that exist in our society, we do invest properly in our schools, we do give all our children a real chance and we do have a health service that is really there for all of us at all times.

53
00:04:57,163 --> 00:04:59,567
[SPEAKER_07]: That's the kind of agenda that I've spent my life dealing with.

54
00:04:59,808 --> 00:05:02,552
[SPEAKER_07]: The gentleman that asked the question about businesses,

55
00:05:02,532 --> 00:05:13,533
[SPEAKER_07]: On the questions of public ownership, which you're quite right to raise, our proposals are that we will take our railways, which after all were invested in and built by the rest of us, back into public ownership.

56
00:05:13,914 --> 00:05:19,545
[SPEAKER_07]: We'll take Royal Mail back into public ownership as it's a natural monopoly and our water industry

57
00:05:19,525 --> 00:05:31,500
[SPEAKER_07]: which has been asset-stripped to within an inch of its life by many of these water companies and wastes a great deal of water will come back into public ownership which will be run with consumer and worker involvement.

58
00:05:31,780 --> 00:05:39,610
[SPEAKER_07]: The new announcement we made last week was on broadband because I believe that the government's proposals are insufficient

59
00:05:39,590 --> 00:05:45,322
[SPEAKER_07]: Only 10% of households in the whole of the UK get access to fibre optic broadband.

60
00:05:45,563 --> 00:05:52,357
[SPEAKER_07]: We will make that 100% within 10 years, starting in the areas, the remote areas of the country, that have the least access at the moment.

61
00:05:52,417 --> 00:05:55,344
[SPEAKER_07]: Hence, we can get the business development done in those places.

62
00:05:55,364 --> 00:05:56,246
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, let's hear a little bit more from him.

63
00:05:56,266 --> 00:05:56,907
[SPEAKER_44]: Just the man in the white shirt.

64
00:06:00,295 --> 00:06:04,199
[SPEAKER_17]: Mr. Corbyn, I heard you talk about free speech and standing up for human rights.

65
00:06:04,580 --> 00:06:06,642
[SPEAKER_17]: And I have two young daughters.

66
00:06:07,263 --> 00:06:13,029
[SPEAKER_17]: And what terrifies me is I look at some of the Labour MPs, some female Labour MPs, and the misogyny that's happened in the Labour Party.

67
00:06:13,069 --> 00:06:14,390
[SPEAKER_17]: They've been driven out the party.

68
00:06:14,831 --> 00:06:22,739
[SPEAKER_17]: I look at a video on YouTube with Ruth Smith, particularly, because I'm willing to give you the benefit of the doubt in terms of maybe people are doing it in your name and not supported by you.

69
00:06:22,759 --> 00:06:26,944
[SPEAKER_17]: But I look at a video of Ruth Smith online, where she was in a press conference with you,

70
00:06:26,924 --> 00:06:30,629
[SPEAKER_17]: And basically, Ruth Smith, a Jewish MP, was heckled out of that press conference.

71
00:06:30,649 --> 00:06:31,690
[SPEAKER_17]: It's online, it's on YouTube.

72
00:06:32,171 --> 00:06:36,897
[SPEAKER_17]: And there you are, at the end of the press conference, chatting happily to that same heckler.

73
00:06:36,917 --> 00:06:39,040
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't buy this whole nice old grandpa.

74
00:06:39,461 --> 00:06:42,064
[SPEAKER_17]: I see that video, and that tells me all I need to know.

75
00:06:42,104 --> 00:06:45,088
[SPEAKER_17]: And I'm terrified for my daughters, because I see what you did in that video.

76
00:06:46,190 --> 00:06:53,380
[SPEAKER_17]: And I don't understand how you can say you stand up for human rights and free speech when that's how you support a Labour MP at a Labour press conference.

77
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:54,321
[SPEAKER_17]: I think it's disgraceful.

78
00:06:54,902 --> 00:06:56,003
[SPEAKER_07]: Nobody should...

79
00:06:57,738 --> 00:07:02,140
[SPEAKER_07]: Nobody should suffer any abuse in public life or privately.

80
00:07:02,502 --> 00:07:03,748
[SPEAKER_17]: Clear.

81
00:07:05,551 --> 00:07:14,079
[SPEAKER_07]: Nobody should suffer abuse, and many women Labour MPs, Ruth Smith included and others, have suffered the most unbelievable levels of abuse.

82
00:07:14,419 --> 00:07:21,926
[SPEAKER_07]: And it was a Labour MP, Jo Cox, who was murdered because she stood up in public life.

83
00:07:22,206 --> 00:07:34,917
[SPEAKER_07]: I simply say to you that bad behaviour, misogynism, racism in any form, is absolutely not acceptable in any form whatsoever in my party or in our society.

84
00:07:37,597 --> 00:07:45,947
[SPEAKER_17]: then why, and it's online, why were you talking happily and with a smile on your face to that same heckler when she's been heckled in tears at the press conference?

85
00:07:46,267 --> 00:07:49,991
[SPEAKER_17]: Why would Labour MPs, female MPs, need bodyguards at a Labour conference?

86
00:07:50,011 --> 00:07:53,095
[SPEAKER_17]: I just don't understand it, but it seems like we're not going to come to an agreement.

87
00:07:53,115 --> 00:07:54,697
[SPEAKER_07]: I've had many conversations with Ruth Smith since then.

88
00:07:54,957 --> 00:07:55,397
[SPEAKER_07]: She's left the party.

89
00:07:55,417 --> 00:08:01,825
[SPEAKER_07]: The gentleman concerned I'd known for many years, and I did say hello to him as I left the meeting, as you would somebody you'd known as well.

90
00:08:01,845 --> 00:08:02,626
[SPEAKER_07]: Go and look at the video, Mr Corbyn.

91
00:08:02,646 --> 00:08:04,768
[SPEAKER_07]: And also, you don't know what was said between us.

92
00:08:04,748 --> 00:08:09,080
[SPEAKER_44]: Go and look at the video, Mr Corbyn, and see if it's fair.

93
00:08:09,160 --> 00:08:19,007
[SPEAKER_44]: Mr Corbyn, under your leadership, Labour has become the second political party after the BNP to be invested by the Equality and Human Rights Commission.

94
00:08:19,027 --> 00:08:20,732
[SPEAKER_44]: How do you feel to be in that kind of company?

95
00:08:20,712 --> 00:08:25,199
[SPEAKER_07]: It's our process that is being looked at and I'm very happy about that.

96
00:08:25,299 --> 00:08:27,262
[SPEAKER_07]: We've laid ourselves completely open to it.

97
00:08:27,583 --> 00:08:36,156
[SPEAKER_07]: We're the party that after all set up the Equality and Human Rights Commission and in government we will fund it properly and I think it's right that our processes should be examined.

98
00:08:36,436 --> 00:08:43,868
[SPEAKER_07]: We're the only party that actually has a full process to deal with abuse, racism in any form.

99
00:08:43,848 --> 00:08:47,805
[SPEAKER_07]: within our party or our society is simply not acceptable.

100
00:08:48,026 --> 00:08:54,212
[SPEAKER_07]: We have suspended and expelled members that have been guilty of any racist activity.

101
00:08:56,993 --> 00:09:08,264
[SPEAKER_08]: Jeremy Corbyn, you've talked about standing by human rights and so on, but recently you took a stance alongside Ivo Morales, who recently resigned and left Bolivia to Mexico.

102
00:09:08,684 --> 00:09:17,313
[SPEAKER_08]: There's protests in Bolivia that have turned violent in support of Ivo Morales, including food blockades that are starving cities like La Paz.

103
00:09:17,433 --> 00:09:25,060
[SPEAKER_08]: So how are you supporting human rights in that regard when you're standing with somebody who has protests that support him, that use such violent means to do so?

104
00:09:25,917 --> 00:09:29,483
[SPEAKER_07]: I met Evo Morales in Mexico last year.

105
00:09:29,663 --> 00:09:37,755
[SPEAKER_07]: I had a very long conversation with him about his country and about the economic development that's happened and the numbers of people that have been taken out of poverty.

106
00:09:38,236 --> 00:09:42,703
[SPEAKER_07]: Obviously, I follow what's going on in that country as I do in many other countries in the world.

107
00:09:43,104 --> 00:09:48,432
[SPEAKER_07]: He resigned from the presidency and now has moved out of Bolivia.

108
00:09:48,412 --> 00:09:59,447
[SPEAKER_07]: I ask and I support the other Latin American governments that have asked for a process of peace in Bolivia so that the Constitution can be restored, so that democratic government can come back.

109
00:09:59,747 --> 00:10:02,010
[SPEAKER_07]: That surely is the right thing to do.

110
00:10:02,111 --> 00:10:03,673
[SPEAKER_08]: I agree, but that's not what you said on Twitter.

111
00:10:03,693 --> 00:10:05,295
[SPEAKER_08]: You said you stand by Ivo Morales.

112
00:10:05,335 --> 00:10:09,120
[SPEAKER_08]: You took a position in something in such a...

113
00:10:09,573 --> 00:10:14,978
[SPEAKER_08]: a dispute right now, a civil unrest, that any opinion, one way or another, is turning violent.

114
00:10:15,258 --> 00:10:19,102
[SPEAKER_08]: So when you take a position in something like that, it emboldens the violence.

115
00:10:19,602 --> 00:10:21,544
[SPEAKER_07]: It's obvious there is civil unrest in Bolivia.

116
00:10:21,564 --> 00:10:31,993
[SPEAKER_07]: There are very strong feelings on both sides about people that feel they've been let down because Evo Morales is no longer president, others that probably don't support him at all.

117
00:10:32,253 --> 00:10:35,016
[SPEAKER_07]: Surely the function now is to try and bring people together.

118
00:10:35,336 --> 00:10:36,717
[SPEAKER_07]: I met Evo Morales last year.

119
00:10:36,737 --> 00:10:39,580
[SPEAKER_07]: I've met him over the years.

120
00:10:39,560 --> 00:10:45,065
[SPEAKER_07]: recognise that Bolivia, before he became president, was probably the poorest country in Latin America.

121
00:10:45,305 --> 00:10:45,886
[SPEAKER_07]: It isn't now.

122
00:10:46,146 --> 00:10:46,467
[SPEAKER_44]: OK.

123
00:10:46,747 --> 00:10:47,447
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm sorry to shut you down.

124
00:10:47,467 --> 00:10:49,149
[SPEAKER_44]: There's a lot of questions people want to get in.

125
00:10:49,189 --> 00:10:50,931
[SPEAKER_44]: Let's hear a question from Daniel Holt.

126
00:10:51,471 --> 00:10:52,532
[SPEAKER_44]: Where are you, Daniel?

127
00:10:52,552 --> 00:10:53,954
[SPEAKER_30]: Up here, yeah.

128
00:10:53,974 --> 00:10:57,337
[SPEAKER_30]: Mr Corbyn, will you campaign to remain or leave in the EU if elected?

129
00:10:57,577 --> 00:11:00,240
[SPEAKER_30]: Why would anyone vote Labour without knowing the answer to that question?

130
00:11:05,485 --> 00:11:05,865
[SPEAKER_07]: APPLAUSE Thank you.

131
00:11:05,885 --> 00:11:07,086
[SPEAKER_07]: Thanks for your question.

132
00:11:07,910 --> 00:11:13,581
[SPEAKER_07]: The issue of Brexit can be one that divides people enormously and it has and it does.

133
00:11:14,423 --> 00:11:21,077
[SPEAKER_07]: Our whole strategy, my whole strategy has been to try to bring people together however they voted in the referendum in 2016.

134
00:11:21,217 --> 00:11:24,223
[SPEAKER_44]: But the question is will you campaign to remain or leave the EU if elected?

135
00:11:24,464 --> 00:11:25,947
[SPEAKER_44]: Can I answer it?

136
00:11:26,147 --> 00:11:28,031
[SPEAKER_44]: No, I'd love you to answer it, that's it.

137
00:11:28,131 --> 00:11:28,652
[SPEAKER_07]: Right.

138
00:11:29,560 --> 00:11:33,267
[SPEAKER_07]: One, we will negotiate a credible leave deal with the European Union.

139
00:11:33,428 --> 00:11:34,390
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me finish, please.

140
00:11:34,450 --> 00:11:36,614
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm trying to answer the gentleman's question.

141
00:11:37,095 --> 00:11:41,283
[SPEAKER_07]: Secondly, we will put that alongside remain in a referendum.

142
00:11:41,724 --> 00:11:50,742
[SPEAKER_07]: My role and the role of our government will be to ensure that that referendum is held in a fair atmosphere, and we will abide by the result of it.

143
00:11:50,722 --> 00:12:06,075
[SPEAKER_07]: and I will adopt, as Prime Minister if I am at the time, a neutral stance so that I can credibly carry out the results of that to bring our communities and country together rather than continuing an endless debate about the EU and Brexit.

144
00:12:06,115 --> 00:12:09,839
[SPEAKER_07]: This will be a trade deal with Europe or remaining in the EU.

145
00:12:09,979 --> 00:12:13,382
[SPEAKER_07]: That will be the choice that we put before the British people within six months.

146
00:12:13,702 --> 00:12:20,408
[SPEAKER_07]: Any other option will require years of negotiations either with the EU or the USA and put our public services at risk.

147
00:12:20,388 --> 00:12:27,774
[SPEAKER_30]: Daniel, does that answer your question?

148
00:12:27,814 --> 00:12:32,811
[SPEAKER_30]: We've already had three and a half years of upheaval and the British people voted in 2016, so why do we need to vote again?

149
00:12:33,044 --> 00:12:40,095
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, I think the demands of people to try to, A, some parties want to revoke Article 50.

150
00:12:40,175 --> 00:12:42,559
[SPEAKER_07]: I actually voted to implement Article 50.

151
00:12:42,820 --> 00:12:45,144
[SPEAKER_07]: Some people wanted a second referendum.

152
00:12:45,244 --> 00:12:51,053
[SPEAKER_07]: Some people wanted leaving without any deal whatsoever, which I think would be catastrophic to our economy.

153
00:12:51,033 --> 00:13:16,703
[SPEAKER_07]: People voted remain, they voted leave but they didn't vote to lose their jobs, they didn't vote for deregulation, they didn't vote for damage to our economy and I think it's only sensible and reasonable to put that option back there to the people within six months in order to bring our country and society together to face the future together to bring about a fairer Britain.

154
00:13:18,556 --> 00:13:26,031
[SPEAKER_48]: I mean, this thing about saying that lots of people are groaning because he's saying that he's not going to take a clear position, there is actually precedence for this.

155
00:13:26,632 --> 00:13:31,282
[SPEAKER_48]: When there was a referendum on Europe in the 1970s, Howard Wilson remained neutral.

156
00:13:32,044 --> 00:13:35,911
[SPEAKER_48]: So for people to say, oh, this is ridiculous that he's not taking a position, it's false.

157
00:13:35,972 --> 00:13:37,695
[SPEAKER_48]: It's a false position.

158
00:13:40,915 --> 00:13:45,483
[SPEAKER_48]: The Liberal Democrats are saying reverse Brexit, stop Brexit.

159
00:13:45,503 --> 00:13:47,706
[SPEAKER_48]: Boris Johnson is saying get Brexit done.

160
00:13:48,047 --> 00:13:58,604
[SPEAKER_48]: The only person that actually has a clear strategy, a grown-up, sensible strategy, is this man right here, Jeremy Corbyn.

161
00:13:58,624 --> 00:14:02,391
[SPEAKER_44]: Just to be clear, Harold Wilson did actually say he was in favour, but he allowed a free vote on it.

162
00:14:02,411 --> 00:14:03,312
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, the woman there.

163
00:14:04,473 --> 00:14:12,025
[SPEAKER_33]: Corbyn, I appreciate your efforts at bringing people together in this country.

164
00:14:12,605 --> 00:14:13,968
[SPEAKER_33]: I understand your strategy.

165
00:14:15,250 --> 00:14:28,590
[SPEAKER_33]: What I'm really interested in is that the Labour Party seems to be the only party which is developing a credible set of policies to deal with climate emergency.

166
00:14:29,971 --> 00:14:42,040
[SPEAKER_33]: Could you enlighten us about what you think your Labour Party policies would do for jobs and for a good future for young people in Sheffield?

167
00:14:42,155 --> 00:14:42,556
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

168
00:14:43,297 --> 00:14:45,021
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you very much for your question.

169
00:14:46,003 --> 00:14:49,710
[SPEAKER_07]: We face a climate emergency across the whole world.

170
00:14:50,291 --> 00:14:51,113
[SPEAKER_07]: It's very obvious.

171
00:14:51,634 --> 00:14:54,259
[SPEAKER_07]: Unusual and extreme weather patterns have got worse and worse.

172
00:14:54,821 --> 00:14:58,708
[SPEAKER_07]: The poorest and most vulnerable people in the poorest and most vulnerable places suffer first.

173
00:14:59,069 --> 00:15:00,973
[SPEAKER_07]: Others suffer later.

174
00:15:00,953 --> 00:15:04,219
[SPEAKER_07]: We signed up to the Paris Climate Change Accords in 2015.

175
00:15:04,319 --> 00:15:09,729
[SPEAKER_07]: I was there, I thought it was great, but it didn't go far enough and it's got to go much further.

176
00:15:10,150 --> 00:15:20,970
[SPEAKER_07]: So on May 1st this year, I proposed to Parliament that we declare a climate emergency in our country and that's now been replicated in many Parliaments around the world and I'm pleased about that.

177
00:15:20,950 --> 00:15:27,176
[SPEAKER_07]: But it does mean we've got to play our part by reducing emissions to get to net zero emissions.

178
00:15:27,496 --> 00:15:35,324
[SPEAKER_07]: It also means the possibilities of a huge number of jobs and development in our country in dealing with this emergency.

179
00:15:35,604 --> 00:15:43,592
[SPEAKER_07]: It means jobs in retrofitting houses to make them environmentally sustainable, to make them better insulated, to use less energy.

180
00:15:43,832 --> 00:15:46,975
[SPEAKER_07]: It means green energy jobs, wind, wave, solar.

181
00:15:46,955 --> 00:15:49,999
[SPEAKER_07]: It means big projects like Swansea Bay Lagoon.

182
00:15:50,079 --> 00:15:56,326
[SPEAKER_07]: It also means a lot has to be done in protecting our biodiversity, our seas and our rivers.

183
00:15:56,607 --> 00:16:06,178
[SPEAKER_07]: And so our whole strategy is to develop a green industrial revolution which will create hundreds of thousands of jobs in the future, starting very, very quickly.

184
00:16:06,538 --> 00:16:12,085
[SPEAKER_07]: And we will be therefore playing our part in getting to a more sustainable world and a Labour government

185
00:16:12,065 --> 00:16:26,266
[SPEAKER_07]: on the international stage, we'll be working with others to get to net zero and make sure that by our trading policies we don't end up inadvertently exporting pollution by having strong controls here but not insisting on equally strong controls somewhere else.

186
00:16:26,526 --> 00:16:26,927
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you very much.

187
00:16:26,947 --> 00:16:37,683
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm very excited by everything that's in our green industrial revolution strategy, just as much as I admire those in the USA with the Green New Deal that they're putting forward.

188
00:16:37,703 --> 00:16:39,726
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, I'm going to take three or four points from the audience in a row, starting the woman over there.

189
00:16:42,777 --> 00:16:46,642
[SPEAKER_43]: I noticed in your opening speech that you mentioned about broadband again.

190
00:16:46,983 --> 00:16:55,714
[SPEAKER_43]: At a time when the NHS is desperately in need of funding and there's not an everlasting pot of money, why do you think that's a good use of taxpayers' money?

191
00:16:55,914 --> 00:16:57,416
[SPEAKER_43]: OK, let's hear from the man behind you then.

192
00:16:58,478 --> 00:17:02,423
[SPEAKER_49]: You said about negotiating another deal after the election.

193
00:17:02,926 --> 00:17:07,450
[SPEAKER_49]: How do we know that the deal you're going to get is going to be any better or even worse than what's already on offer?

194
00:17:07,991 --> 00:17:12,695
[SPEAKER_49]: And therefore, are we being offered something that's not worth having Brexit in the first place?

195
00:17:12,975 --> 00:17:14,076
[SPEAKER_49]: So really, it's not credible.

196
00:17:14,616 --> 00:17:15,677
[SPEAKER_49]: And the woman here in the black top.

197
00:17:17,619 --> 00:17:29,610
[SPEAKER_21]: Mr Corbyn, are you seriously saying that, should you be in government, you would come back with the new deal, it may be better than the Conservatives, it may not be, and then not campaign either way up until the referendum?

198
00:17:30,170 --> 00:17:32,072
[SPEAKER_21]: The Labour Party wouldn't campaign at all.

199
00:17:32,930 --> 00:17:37,377
[SPEAKER_44]: Well, we know some members of the Labour Party, some members of your cabinet would absolutely campaign for remain.

200
00:17:37,397 --> 00:17:38,078
[SPEAKER_44]: They've made it very clear.

201
00:17:38,579 --> 00:17:41,584
[SPEAKER_07]: OK. Can I deal with the broadband question first?

202
00:17:41,624 --> 00:17:42,926
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you for it.

203
00:17:43,367 --> 00:17:51,259
[SPEAKER_07]: The issue is, as I said earlier, 95% of people in South Korea have access to broadband free.

204
00:17:51,800 --> 00:17:56,227
[SPEAKER_07]: We have, in this country, 10% access, and it costs people roughly £30 a month.

205
00:17:56,528 --> 00:17:58,070
[SPEAKER_07]: And it's quite selective, the areas...

206
00:17:58,090 --> 00:17:59,933
[SPEAKER_07]: It's not free in South Korea, though, is it?

207
00:18:00,200 --> 00:18:04,045
[SPEAKER_07]: For some people it is, I'm not sure about the whole country, but it is available for the whole country.

208
00:18:04,406 --> 00:18:10,715
[SPEAKER_07]: Our point is that by investing in it, it actually promotes economic growth and brings about a degree of social justice.

209
00:18:10,735 --> 00:18:18,566
[SPEAKER_07]: Listen, everyone in this room probably has a computer and uses access to broadband if they've got it, or some form of internet all the time.

210
00:18:18,726 --> 00:18:21,550
[SPEAKER_07]: It is the normal form of communication.

211
00:18:21,530 --> 00:18:27,741
[SPEAKER_07]: Yet there is a big digital divide between those that can afford the best and those that don't get any whatsoever.

212
00:18:27,841 --> 00:18:30,185
[SPEAKER_07]: I just want to make sure it's equally available for all.

213
00:18:30,446 --> 00:18:32,509
[SPEAKER_07]: And over 10 years, we would make sure it is.

214
00:18:32,569 --> 00:18:38,079
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think that's actually a sensible, up-to-date, modern way of looking at communications within our society.

215
00:18:38,480 --> 00:18:39,842
[SPEAKER_44]: So the question is, can we afford it?

216
00:18:40,008 --> 00:18:53,228
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, we can afford it, because if we don't afford it, then what's the effect on areas that don't have access to broadband, on their economic development, on the investments that might come there, on the businesses that won't go there?

217
00:18:53,649 --> 00:18:58,676
[SPEAKER_07]: Listen, talk to a business about investing in, say, Cumbria, or, say, parts of Northumbria.

218
00:18:58,716 --> 00:19:02,162
[SPEAKER_07]: Say, would you open a factory or a shop or a small business here?

219
00:19:02,202 --> 00:19:03,163
[SPEAKER_07]: They'd say,

220
00:19:03,143 --> 00:19:08,893
[SPEAKER_07]: No, there's no broadband, there isn't good train access, there isn't good bus access or whatever else.

221
00:19:09,093 --> 00:19:14,923
[SPEAKER_07]: We have to invest in social infrastructure and transport infrastructure for the whole country.

222
00:19:15,283 --> 00:19:23,557
[SPEAKER_07]: Otherwise, the North-South divide, the inequalities between regions in England and between Scotland and Wales and England will simply get worse as a result of it.

223
00:19:23,577 --> 00:19:28,746
[SPEAKER_07]: This is a serious proposal in order to help bring economic development to all parts of our country.

224
00:19:28,726 --> 00:19:45,151
[SPEAKER_44]: And what do you make of the comments made by the Institute of Fiscal Studies today that in order to pay for the broadband and all the other things that you're suggesting, what they're saying is you can't do that by pretending that you're just going to tax the very rich, the top 5%.

225
00:19:45,291 --> 00:19:48,456
[SPEAKER_44]: You're going to have to tax an awful lot more of our audience.

226
00:19:48,436 --> 00:20:00,550
[SPEAKER_07]: I read the IFS comments very carefully obviously and we have here the grey book that we put forward which actually funds and costs the whole of our programme and manifesto and I was absolutely insistent that we as a party going into election put that forward.

227
00:20:00,611 --> 00:20:03,559
[SPEAKER_07]: It's only right that people should understand it.

228
00:20:03,539 --> 00:20:08,666
[SPEAKER_07]: is 95% of the population will pay no more whatsoever in tax.

229
00:20:08,686 --> 00:20:11,449
[SPEAKER_07]: The top 5% will pay a bit more.

230
00:20:11,830 --> 00:20:25,547
[SPEAKER_07]: Corporation tax will go up to a maximum of 26%, which is lower than it was in 2010, and lower than many countries in other parts of the world, including major industrial economies.

231
00:20:25,527 --> 00:20:34,139
[SPEAKER_07]: and we will then move into a situation where we become more or less mid-ranking in terms of provisions of funding of public services.

232
00:20:34,199 --> 00:20:39,106
[SPEAKER_07]: We'll still be way below all the Scandinavian countries, France and Germany.

233
00:20:39,286 --> 00:20:43,452
[SPEAKER_07]: What's happened in this country for too long is we've rolled back

234
00:20:43,432 --> 00:20:44,313
[SPEAKER_07]: the public realm.

235
00:20:44,354 --> 00:20:51,826
[SPEAKER_07]: We've rolled back on public services and loaded that problem onto individuals, families and they're often paying with it through personal debt.

236
00:20:51,966 --> 00:20:59,719
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we need to rebalance a bit and start investing in people and communities as a whole and that's what our manifesto does.

237
00:21:04,829 --> 00:21:05,870
[SPEAKER_36]: Yes, you.

238
00:21:05,890 --> 00:21:06,010
[SPEAKER_52]: Hi.

239
00:21:06,451 --> 00:21:12,138
[SPEAKER_52]: I work for a charity that delivers digital inclusion, and it's not just about broadband, it's more than that.

240
00:21:12,158 --> 00:21:16,483
[SPEAKER_52]: Giving broadband to households is great, but what are we going to do to make sure that we close the gap?

241
00:21:16,503 --> 00:21:21,849
[SPEAKER_52]: People can use Facebook, people can use certain websites, but there's other things they can't do, they can't navigate.

242
00:21:22,149 --> 00:21:27,816
[SPEAKER_52]: Public service websites, NHS advice, how are you going to ensure that people get that as well as broadband access?

243
00:21:28,319 --> 00:21:49,382
[SPEAKER_07]: Well if they've got good quality broadband obviously that's a start and clearly there has to be full accessibility to public services online because there is, you're quite correct, a digital divide where public services increasingly, doctors appointments and everything else are done online and there are a significant number of people in the country that

244
00:21:49,362 --> 00:21:57,656
[SPEAKER_07]: don't necessarily have smartphones, probably don't have computers and can't access those things and that becomes a form of social exclusion.

245
00:21:57,696 --> 00:22:07,472
[SPEAKER_07]: So I would always make it a requirement that public services must be available also in the more traditional ways as well so that nobody is left out because there's nothing worse

246
00:22:07,452 --> 00:22:16,787
[SPEAKER_07]: than people that are told, for example, to go online to sort out their universal credit, can't get online because they haven't got a computer or a smartphone.

247
00:22:17,047 --> 00:22:20,412
[SPEAKER_07]: How on earth are they supposed to access universal credit in that sense?

248
00:22:20,472 --> 00:22:27,283
[SPEAKER_07]: That's why we will end universal credit and bring back a serious system.

249
00:22:30,875 --> 00:22:42,186
[SPEAKER_01]: I know your comment regarding broadband is very good, but one thing I want to ask, you are talking about delaying the Scottish independence referendum and Boris Johnson talking about refusing it.

250
00:22:42,807 --> 00:22:47,992
[SPEAKER_01]: Is the UK like the Hotel California, you can check out any time you want but you can never leave?

251
00:22:48,613 --> 00:22:51,936
[SPEAKER_01]: Another thing, what gives Westminster...

252
00:22:51,956 --> 00:22:56,140
[SPEAKER_01]: The last debate you and the Prime Minister were on, there were two

253
00:22:56,120 --> 00:22:59,385
[SPEAKER_01]: Westminster MPs telling Scotland what they are not getting.

254
00:22:59,785 --> 00:23:02,329
[SPEAKER_01]: Surely we should start listening to the Scottish people first and let us have a vote.

255
00:23:03,170 --> 00:23:06,715
[SPEAKER_44]: Before you answer, Mr Corbyn, I think you might have practised that line before.

256
00:23:06,735 --> 00:23:08,218
[SPEAKER_44]: Let's hear from Max Cruikshank.

257
00:23:08,238 --> 00:23:08,578
[SPEAKER_44]: Where are you?

258
00:23:08,718 --> 00:23:10,181
[SPEAKER_44]: Is that you there?

259
00:23:10,201 --> 00:23:10,761
[SPEAKER_60]: Yes, Jeremy.

260
00:23:10,801 --> 00:23:17,211
[SPEAKER_60]: Scotland voted overwhelmingly against leaving Europe and for pro-independence, pro-independence government.

261
00:23:17,671 --> 00:23:22,178
[SPEAKER_60]: Why will Labour not support us in deciding our own future?

262
00:23:22,951 --> 00:23:27,459
[SPEAKER_07]: OK, thanks for your questions, and thanks for the way that you've put them.

263
00:23:28,240 --> 00:23:37,196
[SPEAKER_07]: An incoming Labour government will invest a great deal across the UK, including 100 billion pounds will go into Scotland over 10 years.

264
00:23:37,496 --> 00:23:43,426
[SPEAKER_07]: That will be a massive game changer in Scotland, where you have the worst levels of poverty and health inequality in Glasgow.

265
00:23:43,767 --> 00:23:46,452
[SPEAKER_07]: You have serious levels of child poverty and housing stress.

266
00:23:46,492 --> 00:23:47,794
[SPEAKER_07]: You know that as well as I do.

267
00:23:47,774 --> 00:23:50,978
[SPEAKER_07]: So the question is, why will you not support it, or will you support a referendum?

268
00:23:50,998 --> 00:23:56,364
