296
00:26:00,559 --> 00:26:06,506
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think you have to look at the situation of the income and expenditure levels as they affect Scotland.

297
00:26:06,766 --> 00:26:07,587
[SPEAKER_07]: Surely

298
00:26:07,567 --> 00:26:16,137
[SPEAKER_07]: Scotland needs to be able to address the problems it has, and the industrial and green infrastructure investment that it absolutely needs.

299
00:26:16,417 --> 00:26:18,139
[SPEAKER_07]: That's all it means, Scotland, they're telling me.

300
00:26:18,940 --> 00:26:23,605
[SPEAKER_44]: I'm sorry, I know you want to make your point, but there's so many hands, it's not fair if I just give it all to you.

301
00:26:23,625 --> 00:26:24,946
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, the man here in the check shirt.

302
00:26:25,387 --> 00:26:35,278
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes, what you're saying is promising things for Scotland to try and avoid another independence referendum.

303
00:26:35,883 --> 00:26:46,580
[SPEAKER_05]: very similar to what happened in 2014 with other promises made by senior Labour members with the fictitious bow.

304
00:26:48,002 --> 00:26:53,170
[SPEAKER_05]: How on earth can we trust that this would not be another case of broken promises?

305
00:26:53,931 --> 00:26:58,017
[SPEAKER_07]: Since 2014 there has been a Tory government in the UK and that is one of the problems.

306
00:26:58,919 --> 00:27:00,321
[SPEAKER_44]: Can we hear from the woman here in the front?

307
00:27:03,980 --> 00:27:19,812
[SPEAKER_58]: In 2014, there was a triple mandate saying that we would be allowed to have a second vote if it went against the will of the people and getting taken out of Europe is against the will of the people in Scotland.

308
00:27:19,994 --> 00:27:20,474
[SPEAKER_44]: Do you mind?

309
00:27:20,494 --> 00:27:24,138
[SPEAKER_44]: I seem to have unerringly found all the stuff in the audience at once.

310
00:27:24,158 --> 00:27:26,220
[SPEAKER_44]: Marvellous to have you here, but there are lots of questions on other things.

311
00:27:26,240 --> 00:27:30,383
[SPEAKER_44]: Will you forgive me if I see if I can... No, not you, matey, cos I know you definitely want to ask about Scotland.

312
00:27:30,423 --> 00:27:31,484
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, at the back.

313
00:27:31,504 --> 00:27:32,625
[SPEAKER_44]: Is your question about Scotland?

314
00:27:33,326 --> 00:27:33,866
[SPEAKER_44]: Slightly.

315
00:27:34,267 --> 00:27:35,508
[SPEAKER_19]: Oh, maybe, then.

316
00:27:35,808 --> 00:27:37,550
[SPEAKER_44]: We have very little time left, so we'll be very brief.

317
00:27:37,730 --> 00:27:46,217
[SPEAKER_19]: So, if you had a choice of getting into power and signing up a deal with the SNP, that's not going to change, then you're not going to say, OK, Nicola, we'll give you what you want so we can get into power.

318
00:27:46,237 --> 00:27:47,278
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, that definitely is about Scotland.

319
00:27:47,298 --> 00:27:48,199
[SPEAKER_44]: Anyone got a question?

320
00:27:48,259 --> 00:27:49,140
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, the man there.

321
00:27:49,863 --> 00:27:50,884
[SPEAKER_12]: It's not about Scotland.

322
00:27:50,944 --> 00:28:05,541
[SPEAKER_12]: I just think, Jeremy, have you finally got an opportunity, after nine years as the Tories, to get rid of the legacy of Thatcher and Blair and the market and the things that are in your manifesto that improve people's lives?

323
00:28:05,601 --> 00:28:07,483
[SPEAKER_12]: The first question was about being frightened.

324
00:28:07,743 --> 00:28:08,344
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm not frightened.

325
00:28:08,364 --> 00:28:13,029
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm only frightened when I see people on the streets, when I see people can't get health care, all those things.

326
00:28:13,309 --> 00:28:15,732
[SPEAKER_12]: Are you finally in a position you win and you can put it right?

327
00:28:18,035 --> 00:28:19,296
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, let's just hear from one mate in the green top at the back.

328
00:28:19,917 --> 00:28:22,541
[SPEAKER_44]: The woman in the green top, right at the back with the glasses on.

329
00:28:23,282 --> 00:28:25,104
[SPEAKER_44]: No, the woman in the back in the green top.

330
00:28:25,124 --> 00:28:25,325
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes.

331
00:28:26,166 --> 00:28:37,362
[SPEAKER_56]: You say that you're not going to increase taxation, but I've read today that in your manifesto it states that you're going to abolish the married persons tax for couples on a lower combined income.

332
00:28:38,163 --> 00:28:39,205
[SPEAKER_56]: I mean, how can that be fair?

333
00:28:39,225 --> 00:28:42,229
[SPEAKER_56]: I mean, in the last year it cost something like £480 million.

334
00:28:43,150 --> 00:28:45,874
[SPEAKER_56]: That's a drop in the ocean compared to what else you're planning on spending.

335
00:28:46,883 --> 00:28:47,524
[SPEAKER_07]: OK.

336
00:28:48,024 --> 00:28:49,726
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll try and deal with some of those questions, if I may.

337
00:28:49,746 --> 00:28:51,708
[SPEAKER_07]: You've got about a minute left, I'm afraid, Mr Corbyn.

338
00:28:51,868 --> 00:28:53,049
[SPEAKER_44]: You've got about a minute left.

339
00:28:53,069 --> 00:28:55,131
[SPEAKER_44]: You're going to have to do a quick fire round of answering those.

340
00:28:55,191 --> 00:28:57,754
[SPEAKER_07]: First of all, we're not doing any deals with any other parties.

341
00:28:57,794 --> 00:28:59,496
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not trying to form a coalition government.

342
00:28:59,516 --> 00:29:11,348
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm fighting this election to win it for Labour, to win it for the people of this country, to end universal credit, deal with the issues of inequality, injustice and poverty, and deliver an economy that absolutely works for all.

343
00:29:11,648 --> 00:29:16,553
[SPEAKER_07]: And our taxation proposals will affect the richest 5% of the people in this country.

344
00:29:16,533 --> 00:29:28,166
[SPEAKER_07]: We will end the marriage tax allowance because I think it's discriminatory against non-married couples and it ought to be treated equally across the society and individual taxation is a fairer way of doing things.

345
00:29:28,546 --> 00:29:41,260
[SPEAKER_07]: Our manifesto, fully prepared, fully costed, I think this is an opportunity for our country to come together, deal with the inequality, injustice and poverty and actually go forward to the future with some real degree of hope.

346
00:29:41,541 --> 00:29:42,642
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you very much.

347
00:29:44,815 --> 00:29:56,703
[SPEAKER_44]: And just to be clear, in a yes or no answer, you are telling us tonight that you will remain... Just to be clear, in a yes or no answer, you're telling us tonight you will remain neutral on the issue of whether or not we should remain within the EU.

348
00:29:56,723 --> 00:29:58,166
[SPEAKER_44]: First heard here on Question Time.

349
00:29:58,186 --> 00:29:59,008
[SPEAKER_44]: First heard here on Question Time.

350
00:29:59,028 --> 00:30:00,732
[SPEAKER_44]: Mr Corbyn, thank you very much indeed.

351
00:30:19,544 --> 00:30:20,327
[SPEAKER_44]: There we are.

352
00:30:20,527 --> 00:30:25,222
[SPEAKER_44]: So don't forget, in half an hour, we'll be hearing from Jo Swinson, and after that, Boris Johnson.

353
00:30:25,262 --> 00:30:32,305
[SPEAKER_44]: But now, can we please welcome the First Minister of Scotland and leader of the Scottish National Party, Nicola Sturgeon.

354
00:30:42,511 --> 00:30:43,472
[SPEAKER_44]: Good evening, First Minister.

355
00:30:43,492 --> 00:30:43,753
[SPEAKER_44]: Good evening.

356
00:30:43,773 --> 00:30:45,535
[SPEAKER_44]: We are delighted, of course, to have you here.

357
00:30:45,816 --> 00:30:48,880
[SPEAKER_44]: I'm going to say the same thing to you as I'm saying to all the party leaders.

358
00:30:48,900 --> 00:30:55,589
[SPEAKER_44]: The aim is to allow time for our lovely audience here, who've got lots of questions, lots of opinions already, to put as many points to you as possible.

359
00:30:55,609 --> 00:30:58,734
[SPEAKER_44]: So I'll be grateful if you keep your answers brief and to the point.

360
00:30:58,894 --> 00:31:00,737
[SPEAKER_44]: And forgive me if I interrupt you... Of course.

361
00:31:00,757 --> 00:31:01,458
[SPEAKER_44]: ..if you don't.

362
00:31:01,898 --> 00:31:06,324
[SPEAKER_44]: So, let's take our first question for Nicola Sturgeon from Shirley Duncan.

363
00:31:06,404 --> 00:31:07,506
[SPEAKER_44]: Where are you?

364
00:31:07,486 --> 00:31:08,650
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, Shirley Duncan.

365
00:31:08,670 --> 00:31:15,133
[SPEAKER_26]: Sturgeon, if there is a hung Parliament, what is the price of your cooperation with a minority government?

366
00:31:15,839 --> 00:31:19,622
[SPEAKER_39]: Obviously, it is a very good and relevant question for everybody across the UK.

367
00:31:19,723 --> 00:31:24,587
[SPEAKER_39]: The SNP may well hold the balance of power in a hung Parliament after this election.

368
00:31:24,887 --> 00:31:37,479
[SPEAKER_39]: Let me say, we will use that influence, if we have it, responsibly and in the interests, of course, of standing up for Scotland, but also in the interests of progressive values for people right across the UK.

369
00:31:38,039 --> 00:31:44,125
[SPEAKER_39]: Let me be very honest, I could not, in good conscience, ever put Boris Johnson into number 10 Downing Street.

370
00:31:49,572 --> 00:31:56,725
[SPEAKER_39]: because I have seen the misery that Tory policies have heaped upon people.

371
00:31:56,745 --> 00:32:01,334
[SPEAKER_39]: Jeremy Corbyn may not be my choice of Labour leader but I don't get to choose the Labour leader.

372
00:32:01,835 --> 00:32:08,728
[SPEAKER_39]: In terms of what I would seek to win from a minority Labour government, obviously I would

373
00:32:08,708 --> 00:32:14,656
[SPEAKER_39]: ask for and expect Jeremy Corbyn to respect the right of the Scottish people to choose their own future.

374
00:32:14,736 --> 00:32:18,221
[SPEAKER_39]: Because it is not for Westminster to decide, it is for the people of Scotland.

375
00:32:18,522 --> 00:32:20,785
[SPEAKER_39]: But I would also want an end to austerity.

376
00:32:21,185 --> 00:32:24,710
[SPEAKER_39]: I would want to see an end to the misery of universal credit.

377
00:32:25,031 --> 00:32:31,560
[SPEAKER_39]: I would want to see an NHS protection bill so that our NHS cannot be put at the mercy of Donald Trump in a trade deal.

378
00:32:31,540 --> 00:32:34,042
[SPEAKER_39]: I would want to see fairer pensions for our older people.

379
00:32:34,423 --> 00:32:37,085
[SPEAKER_39]: The UK has one of the lowest pensions in the OECD.

380
00:32:37,105 --> 00:32:44,412
[SPEAKER_39]: So these are the progressive policies that the SNP would champion, yes, for people in Scotland, but also for the benefit of people right across the UK.

381
00:32:44,592 --> 00:32:48,455
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, well, let's come back to this independence referendum, what you talked about already at some point.

382
00:32:48,695 --> 00:32:57,103
[SPEAKER_44]: We've just heard the Labour leader saying that he would not offer you a second independence referendum for at least two years of a Labour government.

383
00:32:57,163 --> 00:33:00,366
[SPEAKER_44]: You said, or you have said many times, you want to do that next year.

384
00:33:00,686 --> 00:33:01,547
[SPEAKER_44]: So how's that going to work?

385
00:33:01,527 --> 00:33:06,675
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, you know, firstly, let me explain my position, and then I'll perhaps speculate on Jeremy Corbyn's, if I may.

386
00:33:06,775 --> 00:33:09,699
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, you don't need to speculate, because he told us right here, so would you accept it?

387
00:33:09,719 --> 00:33:13,845
[SPEAKER_39]: I'll speculate on what his position might be after the election, as opposed to what he said here today.

388
00:33:13,865 --> 00:33:14,666
[SPEAKER_39]: Oh, I see.

389
00:33:14,847 --> 00:33:15,047
[SPEAKER_39]: OK.

390
00:33:15,187 --> 00:33:17,831
[SPEAKER_39]: But my position is one of principle.

391
00:33:17,851 --> 00:33:21,256
[SPEAKER_39]: There'll be differences of opinion in this room on Scottish independence.

392
00:33:21,296 --> 00:33:25,002
[SPEAKER_39]: Of course there is a difference of opinion in Scotland on Scottish independence.

393
00:33:25,022 --> 00:33:28,547
[SPEAKER_39]: I would not be asking Jeremy Corbyn to support independence.

394
00:33:28,527 --> 00:33:35,155
[SPEAKER_39]: but simply to accept the principle that that is a question that should be decided by the people of Scotland, not by Westminster.

395
00:33:35,575 --> 00:33:45,107
[SPEAKER_39]: Now, I guess, if I can turn to the position that I think Jeremy Corbyn might take after an election, I've heard some of what Jeremy Corbyn has been saying to you this evening.

396
00:33:45,167 --> 00:33:46,308
[SPEAKER_39]: He spoke with a lot of passion.

397
00:33:46,328 --> 00:33:53,657
[SPEAKER_39]: I don't agree with him on everything, but I do agree with a great deal of what he was talking about, about public spending, health, austerity...

398
00:33:53,677 --> 00:33:55,699
[SPEAKER_39]: But the key thing, as you said, not for the first two years.

399
00:33:55,679 --> 00:33:57,381
[SPEAKER_39]: But that's the point I'm coming on to.

400
00:33:57,401 --> 00:34:13,544
[SPEAKER_39]: I'm asking you, having heard Jeremy Corbyn, do you think he's going to walk away from the chance to end austerity, to protect the NHS, to stop universal credit, simply because he wants, for a couple of years, to prevent Scotland to have the right to self-determination?

401
00:34:13,584 --> 00:34:18,070
[SPEAKER_39]: Jeremy Corbyn supports the right of self-determination for almost every other country in the world.

402
00:34:18,430 --> 00:34:22,816
[SPEAKER_39]: I'm not sure he's going to compromise the chance to have a Labour government for that issue.

403
00:34:22,876 --> 00:34:24,859
[SPEAKER_44]: So you think he's saying one thing to our audience,

404
00:34:24,839 --> 00:34:27,984
[SPEAKER_44]: and to everyone at home, and he's going to be saying another thing to you privately.

405
00:34:28,004 --> 00:34:31,009
[SPEAKER_39]: Look, you're putting it maybe more bluntly, I will be more diplomatic.

406
00:34:31,029 --> 00:34:32,090
[SPEAKER_39]: Just calling it like it is.

407
00:34:32,371 --> 00:34:40,924
[SPEAKER_39]: But the point is, I lead a minority government in Scotland, so I know the compromises that you have to make to govern in that situation.

408
00:34:40,904 --> 00:34:50,719
[SPEAKER_39]: Of course he is putting a manifesto forward, but if he is in the position of needing the support of the SNP, then I think he will choose to do some of the things that are in his manifesto.

409
00:34:50,759 --> 00:34:56,208
[SPEAKER_39]: I don't think he will turn his back on that in order to block the right of the people of Scotland to choose their own future.

410
00:34:56,228 --> 00:34:58,511
[SPEAKER_39]: I would ask you to make your own minds up on that.

411
00:34:59,052 --> 00:35:00,654
[SPEAKER_39]: The man here in the front.

412
00:35:00,675 --> 00:35:06,844
[SPEAKER_54]: So are you saying that you would prioritise the Scottish independence referendum over ending austerity?

413
00:35:07,634 --> 00:35:11,140
[SPEAKER_39]: I want the Scottish people to have the right to choose their own future.

414
00:35:11,481 --> 00:35:18,794
[SPEAKER_39]: Fundamentally for Scotland, we have put up with... Scotland has not voted for a Conservative Westminster Government for 60 years.

415
00:35:19,375 --> 00:35:24,664
[SPEAKER_39]: For 36 of those 60 years, we have had to put up with a Tory Government.

416
00:35:24,644 --> 00:35:26,167
[SPEAKER_39]: the European Union against our will.

417
00:35:26,448 --> 00:35:28,793
[SPEAKER_39]: I want Scotland to determine our own future.

418
00:35:28,893 --> 00:35:34,124
[SPEAKER_39]: But in answer to your question, I will never put a Tory Prime Minister into power.

419
00:35:34,284 --> 00:35:35,526
[SPEAKER_39]: I grew up in the west of Scotland.

420
00:35:35,587 --> 00:35:36,488
[SPEAKER_39]: I saw the damage.

421
00:35:36,549 --> 00:35:38,112
[SPEAKER_39]: I grew up in the Thatcher years.

422
00:35:38,152 --> 00:35:43,082
[SPEAKER_39]: I saw the damage that Tory governments did to Scotland and to communities across the UK.

423
00:35:43,142 --> 00:35:45,066
[SPEAKER_39]: I will never support a Tory government.

424
00:35:45,046 --> 00:35:55,765
[SPEAKER_39]: But if Jeremy Corbyn wants the support of the SNP, I don't think it should surprise people to hear me say that I would ask him to respect the right of the people of Scotland to choose their own future.

425
00:35:56,085 --> 00:36:00,032
[SPEAKER_39]: And I don't think he'll turn his back on ending austerity in order to block that right.

426
00:36:00,433 --> 00:36:01,875
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, well, you heard it here, folks.

427
00:36:02,256 --> 00:36:05,622
[SPEAKER_44]: I'm going to take a few questions, if you don't mind, and then perhaps you can answer them in a row.

428
00:36:05,882 --> 00:36:06,784
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, the woman here.

429
00:36:07,017 --> 00:36:08,699
[SPEAKER_24]: Hello, yes, good evening.

430
00:36:09,220 --> 00:36:15,167
[SPEAKER_24]: At the moment, the talk is that the UK government are focusing too much on Brexit and negating other issues.

431
00:36:15,247 --> 00:36:17,070
[SPEAKER_24]: But don't you think that's happened in Scotland?

432
00:36:17,731 --> 00:36:22,056
[SPEAKER_24]: Jeremy Corbyn actually just brought up that social inequality is huge.

433
00:36:22,116 --> 00:36:25,140
[SPEAKER_24]: I know that knife crime in Glasgow particularly is a big problem.

434
00:36:25,580 --> 00:36:32,349
[SPEAKER_24]: Do you not think by leading with Scottish independence, you're actually negating other issues, like the UK government are doing now with Brexit?

435
00:36:32,589 --> 00:36:34,291
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, let's take a couple more before you answer.

436
00:36:34,532 --> 00:36:35,573
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, the man here.

437
00:36:37,730 --> 00:37:00,925
[SPEAKER_50]: similar, I suppose, but just around if there is a Labour government that you are supporting in coalition and that Labour government takes us through a second referendum and we don't leave Europe, given that the Labour mandate does correspond with yours quite so well, will you still be pushing for an independence referendum for Scotland?

438
00:37:01,486 --> 00:37:02,387
[SPEAKER_44]: And just the men at the back.

439
00:37:03,245 --> 00:37:07,271
[SPEAKER_04]: Over the past few years, we've all borne witness to the farce of a Brexit negotiation.

440
00:37:07,832 --> 00:37:22,536
[SPEAKER_04]: So if Scotland were to get its referendum and it were to win, what guarantees could you make to the rest of the union that we wouldn't see the horrible result of the Brexit negotiations with the to-ing and fro-ing of the hard borders and customs unions and things like that?

441
00:37:23,393 --> 00:37:26,336
[SPEAKER_44]: OK. Lots of different questions you'd like to try and address.

442
00:37:26,476 --> 00:37:28,398
[SPEAKER_39]: I will try to do it as briefly as possible.

443
00:37:28,438 --> 00:37:35,045
[SPEAKER_39]: On the question, very good question, about are we prioritising independence over other issues, I would say that the evidence says no.

444
00:37:36,246 --> 00:37:39,890
[SPEAKER_39]: Don't get me wrong, Scotland has challenges, all countries have challenges.

445
00:37:39,970 --> 00:37:45,576
[SPEAKER_39]: As First Minister, I face challenges in our public services every single day and my job is to confront those.

446
00:37:45,896 --> 00:37:51,662
[SPEAKER_39]: But if you look at some of the policies... Well, if you look at some of the policies in Labour's manifesto published this week,

447
00:37:51,642 --> 00:38:04,193
[SPEAKER_39]: If you take things like free prescriptions, free university education, restoring the nursing bursary, opposition to fracking, for example, these are all things that my government in Scotland has already done.

448
00:38:04,773 --> 00:38:12,720
[SPEAKER_39]: So we're getting on with delivering those progressive policies, but we want to be in charge of our own future, not to turn our backs on the rest of the UK.

449
00:38:12,760 --> 00:38:21,548
[SPEAKER_39]: We'll always be the closest friends and neighbours, but so that we don't get dragged down paths by Tory governments that we don't want to go down.

450
00:38:21,528 --> 00:38:28,218
[SPEAKER_39]: The second question on if there is a second EU referendum and the UK votes to remain.

451
00:38:28,819 --> 00:38:29,660
[SPEAKER_39]: I hope that happens.

452
00:38:29,921 --> 00:38:38,954
[SPEAKER_39]: I've campaigned and worked as hard as possible, as has the SNP, to try to find a way for the whole UK to stay in the EU, because I think that's the best future.

453
00:38:39,215 --> 00:38:44,683
[SPEAKER_44]: And then you won't need to call for a second independence referendum, because there won't be the material change that you talked about last time.

454
00:38:44,663 --> 00:38:47,326
[SPEAKER_44]: which you need, according to yourself, to have one.

455
00:38:47,366 --> 00:38:50,850
[SPEAKER_39]: The case for independence doesn't rest solely on Brexit.

456
00:38:50,870 --> 00:39:00,160
[SPEAKER_39]: Brexit is one example, it's a very extreme example of the way in which Scotland is treated with contempt often by Westminster.

457
00:39:00,641 --> 00:39:02,182
[SPEAKER_39]: And we've seen that over the past three years.

458
00:39:02,202 --> 00:39:07,288
[SPEAKER_39]: We've tried to compromise, we've tried to find ways to protect Scotland's interests, and that hasn't happened.

459
00:39:07,308 --> 00:39:10,992
[SPEAKER_39]: So I think Scotland does need to make that choice about taking a future

460
00:39:10,972 --> 00:39:12,314
[SPEAKER_39]: into our own hands.

461
00:39:12,774 --> 00:39:19,402
[SPEAKER_39]: And thirdly, because this is a very good question about, you know, will independence be as difficult as Brexit?

462
00:39:19,422 --> 00:39:21,564
[SPEAKER_39]: And, you know, I... You've probably noticed this.

463
00:39:21,624 --> 00:39:22,485
[SPEAKER_39]: I oppose Brexit.

464
00:39:22,505 --> 00:39:24,167
[SPEAKER_39]: I think Brexit is a big mistake.

465
00:39:24,467 --> 00:39:29,954
[SPEAKER_39]: But what I don't think is that the mess that Brexit has become was inevitable.

466
00:39:30,334 --> 00:39:38,223
[SPEAKER_39]: That was down to the fact that the Brexiteers, if I can be undiplomatic for a moment, told a lot of lies, one of them on the side of a bus.

467
00:39:38,924 --> 00:39:39,865
[SPEAKER_39]: It was down...

468
00:39:43,388 --> 00:39:54,219
[SPEAKER_39]: down to the fact that there was no honesty or frankness about the implications, no planning done in advance, and then Theresa May came out with all these contradictory red lines that could never be reconciled.

469
00:39:54,920 --> 00:39:58,063
[SPEAKER_39]: Contrast that with the independence referendum in 2014.

470
00:39:58,444 --> 00:40:02,028
[SPEAKER_39]: Whether you agreed with the proposition or not, there was a very detailed proposition.

471
00:40:02,088 --> 00:40:09,075
[SPEAKER_39]: We had done the work, we had done the thinking, we had a whole transition programme ready to go had the result gone the other way.

472
00:40:09,055 --> 00:40:16,729
[SPEAKER_39]: I don't think we should allow the Brexiteers, who made such a hash of Brexit, to tar all positive change with their brush.

473
00:40:16,749 --> 00:40:17,510
[SPEAKER_39]: They messed it up.

474
00:40:17,771 --> 00:40:19,935
[SPEAKER_39]: It doesn't mean others have to mess it up as well.

475
00:40:20,015 --> 00:40:22,980
[SPEAKER_39]: And you want a confirmatory referendum on Brexit.

476
00:40:23,939 --> 00:40:28,025
[SPEAKER_44]: Would you also want a confirmatory referendum on your independence deal by the same token?

477
00:40:28,086 --> 00:40:30,269
[SPEAKER_39]: That is actually connected to the answer I've just given.

478
00:40:30,309 --> 00:40:32,032
[SPEAKER_39]: Oh, I didn't hear that answer.

479
00:40:32,052 --> 00:40:35,037
[SPEAKER_44]: Would you want a confirmatory referendum on your independence deal?

480
00:40:35,057 --> 00:40:43,089
[SPEAKER_39]: If you'll let me answer it in my own terms, if I may, because I was drawing the contrast between the mess of Brexit and the different approach taken for independence.

481
00:40:43,350 --> 00:40:49,359
[SPEAKER_39]: I don't think it was inevitable that Brexit was a mess, therefore I don't think it was inevitable that we were in the position of having another referendum.

482
00:40:49,379 --> 00:40:51,162
[SPEAKER_44]: So would you want a confirmatory referendum?

483
00:40:51,142 --> 00:40:59,332
[SPEAKER_39]: I don't think the position we are in right now with Brexit had to be like this.

484
00:40:59,512 --> 00:41:05,640
[SPEAKER_39]: That was down to the bad planning, the lack of planning, which I don't think the proponents of independence would allow to happen.

485
00:41:06,060 --> 00:41:07,422
[SPEAKER_39]: Can we hear from Rebecca Ferguson?

486
00:41:08,042 --> 00:41:11,867
[SPEAKER_47]: I would like to know,

487
00:41:12,758 --> 00:41:26,581
[SPEAKER_47]: perspective of maybe if we leave the EU or not, if you are denied by government a second independence referendum for Scotland, what particular action will you take following that decision?

488
00:41:26,702 --> 00:41:37,500
[SPEAKER_47]: And whether that's because they've said no or whether because maybe Jeremy Corbyn's government are dragging their heels and it's going on and you were promised but you're not quite getting it, what action will you take?

489
00:41:37,480 --> 00:41:46,069
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, you know, people understandably ask me that all the time, and what I say, and I know it sounds like a typical politician's way of avoiding the answer before I say it is... Oh, no, we don't want that.

490
00:41:46,230 --> 00:41:47,091
[SPEAKER_39]: Well... Not tonight.

491
00:41:47,111 --> 00:41:54,939
[SPEAKER_39]: I know, because I genuinely don't like to answer questions that way, but if I come to that point, then I'll set out how I'll cross that bridge when I come to it.

492
00:41:55,260 --> 00:42:04,770
[SPEAKER_39]: And, yes, I've thought a lot about that, but I don't want to talk about that right now, because that is me conceding that these Westminster politicians actually have a right to block

493
00:42:04,750 --> 00:42:17,063
[SPEAKER_39]: Scotland's ability to choose our own future and actually we're in an election campaign right now and people in Scotland have an opportunity to send a very clear message that they want to be in charge of their own future and that's what I'm asking them to do.

494
00:42:17,103 --> 00:42:18,928
[SPEAKER_39]: But the government does have a right to block it.

495
00:42:19,246 --> 00:42:20,829
[SPEAKER_39]: Your government has the veto on it.

496
00:42:20,889 --> 00:42:24,615
[SPEAKER_39]: I don't think they have a moral or a democratic right to block the right.

497
00:42:24,655 --> 00:42:27,039
[SPEAKER_39]: It has never been legally challenged.

498
00:42:27,059 --> 00:42:33,731
[SPEAKER_39]: I have always accepted and I continue to accept that the transfer of power is necessary and desirable.

499
00:42:34,131 --> 00:42:36,896
[SPEAKER_39]: But I don't believe they have a moral or democratic right.

500
00:42:36,936 --> 00:42:42,165
[SPEAKER_39]: We are in an election campaign and there is an opportunity for Scotland to make that abundantly clear.

501
00:42:42,145 --> 00:43:08,406
[SPEAKER_47]: Surely if obviously you said you were trying not to give a politician's answer because it would be almost conceding defeat like they had a right to block the will of the Scottish people but surely for people in Scotland it would give them confidence that you will see through what they want if you actually set out your contingency plans for if it's denied to you surely you would want to bring Scotland together and actually tell them actually

502
00:43:08,386 --> 00:43:15,576
[SPEAKER_47]: we are our own country, we have a right to determine our own future and this is what we will do if we are denied it by this way.

503
00:43:15,596 --> 00:43:29,196
[SPEAKER_39]: No I think that's a fair point but what I'm saying to Scotland right now and as I said if I come to that point then I will set out exactly to people in Scotland what I think we should do then but what I'm saying to Scotland now in a general election campaign is we have the ability to

504
00:43:29,176 --> 00:43:32,902
[SPEAKER_39]: to send that message and make that view and that voice very clear.

505
00:43:32,922 --> 00:43:35,906
[SPEAKER_39]: And that's what I hope people in Scotland will do for that reason.

506
00:43:35,946 --> 00:43:41,835
[SPEAKER_39]: But I also hope they'll vote SNP so that we can contribute to all of these other social and economic policies that I've been talking about.

507
00:43:42,056 --> 00:43:42,797
[SPEAKER_39]: OK, there's a few hands up.

508
00:43:42,817 --> 00:43:46,763
[SPEAKER_44]: Let's hear from the man there in the blue sweater.

509
00:43:47,131 --> 00:43:53,979
[SPEAKER_59]: In the 2014 referendum, the EU turned around to Scotland and said if they voted for independence, we'd be classed as a third state.

510
00:43:54,300 --> 00:44:00,247
[SPEAKER_59]: So they'd be out basically voting to leave the EU in a sense, and they'd have to rejoin as an independent nation.

511
00:44:00,267 --> 00:44:01,368
[SPEAKER_59]: How would you get around that?

512
00:44:01,669 --> 00:44:08,697
[SPEAKER_59]: You argue that you're so against Brexit and so on, but surely your own independence is another form of Brexit.

513
00:44:08,717 --> 00:44:12,622
[SPEAKER_59]: And also, alongside that, Scotland has the issue of its deficit.

514
00:44:12,742 --> 00:44:15,045
[SPEAKER_59]: How would you get Scotland's deficit down

515
00:44:15,025 --> 00:44:18,335
[SPEAKER_59]: to levels that would be acceptable for the EU to admit you.

516
00:44:18,696 --> 00:44:19,980
[SPEAKER_59]: And you've got the issue of Spain.

517
00:44:20,301 --> 00:44:25,758
[SPEAKER_59]: Would Spain admit you when they've got their own issues with separatists in Catalonia?

518
00:44:26,299 --> 00:44:27,583
[SPEAKER_59]: How will you get round that?

519
00:44:27,766 --> 00:44:30,252
[SPEAKER_44]: Scotland has the largest deficit in Europe at 7%.

520
00:44:30,452 --> 00:44:32,056
[SPEAKER_44]: It needs to be 3% or less.

521
00:44:32,497 --> 00:44:35,644
[SPEAKER_39]: Can I take the gentleman's questions in turn?

522
00:44:36,827 --> 00:44:39,994
[SPEAKER_39]: There are a lot of questions in there, let me try to take them in turn.

523
00:44:40,476 --> 00:44:43,683
[SPEAKER_39]: Firstly, with the greatest of respect, Europe did not say that in 2014.

524
00:44:43,783 --> 00:44:45,808
[SPEAKER_39]: Europe did not make any

525
00:44:45,788 --> 00:44:49,794
[SPEAKER_39]: comment about what would happen if Scotland voted for independence.

526
00:44:49,834 --> 00:44:54,021
[SPEAKER_39]: It certainly didn't say that Scotland would not be allowed to be a member of the European Union.

527
00:44:54,041 --> 00:44:58,288
[SPEAKER_39]: Some may have taken from their body language, they weren't that keen on it, but they didn't actually say that.

528
00:44:58,348 --> 00:45:03,696
[SPEAKER_39]: Nor has Spain ever said that it would veto the membership of an independent Scotland.

529
00:45:03,736 --> 00:45:10,547
[SPEAKER_39]: What Spain has said is that if it is done constitutionally and legally, they would respect that.

530
00:45:10,527 --> 00:45:21,003
[SPEAKER_39]: and I travel a lot around the European Union and there's been a sea change in attitudes towards Scottish independence since Brexit, both in the institutions and in member states.

531
00:45:21,323 --> 00:45:26,030
[SPEAKER_39]: The European Union, since it was first established, has sought to enlarge itself.

532
00:45:26,070 --> 00:45:34,943
[SPEAKER_39]: I think the idea that it's going to try to kick out or not allow in part of a member state that has been there for 40 years is kind of inconceivable.

533
00:45:35,544 --> 00:45:39,370
[SPEAKER_39]: On the deficit, can I firstly make this point?

534
00:45:39,350 --> 00:45:44,236
[SPEAKER_39]: Exclude London, because London skews a lot of the economic calculations for the UK.

535
00:45:44,616 --> 00:45:48,521
[SPEAKER_39]: Scotland's deficit is not out of sync with the rest of the UK.

536
00:45:48,541 --> 00:45:50,143
[SPEAKER_39]: But the thing is, London is in the UK.

537
00:45:50,223 --> 00:45:56,670
[SPEAKER_39]: OK, but in terms of... Because Scotland is often treated as an outlier, London is actually the outlier and Scotland is in line.

538
00:45:56,690 --> 00:46:01,476
[SPEAKER_39]: But that is... We'll leave that point to one side, because I can see I'm not convincing you.

539
00:46:01,456 --> 00:46:02,717
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, what about you?

540
00:46:02,737 --> 00:46:04,559
[SPEAKER_39]: I mean, it doesn't really matter if it's convincing me.

541
00:46:04,679 --> 00:46:08,023
[SPEAKER_39]: OK, but the other point is Scotland's deficit is falling.

542
00:46:08,083 --> 00:46:10,946
[SPEAKER_39]: It fell by £1 billion in the most recent year.

543
00:46:11,026 --> 00:46:14,310
[SPEAKER_39]: Our onshore revenues went up by £3 billion.

544
00:46:14,370 --> 00:46:16,212
[SPEAKER_39]: But my more fundamental point is this.

545
00:46:16,752 --> 00:46:26,503
[SPEAKER_39]: If the argument against independence is that Scotland has a big deficit, that is a deficit that has been accrued under the Westminster system of governance.

546
00:46:26,523 --> 00:46:30,687
[SPEAKER_39]: And if we've got a big deficit because of that, that's not an argument for Scotland staying the same.

547
00:46:30,667 --> 00:46:33,512
[SPEAKER_44]: So what responsibility do you take for that?

548
00:46:33,532 --> 00:46:37,819
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, I don't control, as First Minister, the macroeconomic policies of the United Kingdom.

549
00:46:38,220 --> 00:46:41,365
[SPEAKER_39]: I wish I did in some respects, but I don't.

550
00:46:42,006 --> 00:46:47,415
[SPEAKER_39]: So Scotland does not take all of the decisions in our own government that govern these things.

551
00:46:47,475 --> 00:46:55,729
[SPEAKER_39]: But the point I'm making is, if you look at independent countries similar in size to Scotland all over Europe, they're richer, they're more prosperous,

552
00:46:55,709 --> 00:47:05,145
[SPEAKER_39]: Why shouldn't Scotland, with all the natural and human and social resources we have, be capable of emulating that if we have the powers to do that within our own hands?

553
00:47:05,866 --> 00:47:06,227
[SPEAKER_39]: Thank you.

554
00:47:10,094 --> 00:47:14,101
[SPEAKER_25]: Who ever promised once in a generation referendum?

555
00:47:14,121 --> 00:47:16,705
[SPEAKER_57]: Look, democracy...

556
00:47:17,174 --> 00:47:18,095
[SPEAKER_25]: Who ever promised it?

557
00:47:18,395 --> 00:47:21,598
[SPEAKER_25]: I hear it from Boris Johnson, I hear it from Corbyn.

558
00:47:22,419 --> 00:47:24,841
[SPEAKER_25]: Who actually promised once in a generation?

559
00:47:24,861 --> 00:47:28,105
[SPEAKER_39]: Look, if Brexit hadn't happened, do I think right now...

560
00:47:28,125 --> 00:47:29,646
[SPEAKER_39]: I would still support independence, OK?

561
00:47:29,706 --> 00:47:31,108
[SPEAKER_39]: I'm not going to pretend otherwise.

562
00:47:31,768 --> 00:47:36,913
[SPEAKER_39]: But do I think right now we'd be standing here talking about having another independence referendum so imminently?

563
00:47:37,294 --> 00:47:37,934
[SPEAKER_39]: Probably not.

564
00:47:38,254 --> 00:47:40,957
[SPEAKER_39]: But circumstances have changed dramatically.

565
00:47:41,017 --> 00:47:42,058
[SPEAKER_39]: And in a democracy...

566
00:47:42,078 --> 00:47:42,979
[SPEAKER_25]: Anybody say promise?

567
00:47:42,959 --> 00:47:48,717
[SPEAKER_39]: In a democracy, when circumstances change, people have to have the right to change their mind.

568
00:47:49,139 --> 00:47:55,298
[SPEAKER_39]: And if they don't have that right, then I don't believe what we're living in is a democracy.

569
00:47:59,311 --> 00:48:04,682
[SPEAKER_39]: I can't force Scotland to choose independence just as I can't force the UK to stay in the EU.

570
00:48:04,722 --> 00:48:14,481
[SPEAKER_39]: But I do believe we should have that choice so that whatever path we take as a country, whatever kind of country we are going to become, it's one we've chosen ourselves.

571
00:48:14,562 --> 00:48:17,447
[SPEAKER_39]: It's not one that we've had the likes of Boris Johnson decide for us.

572
00:48:17,527 --> 00:48:19,311
[SPEAKER_25]: But was the word promise used?

573
00:48:19,291 --> 00:48:20,454
[SPEAKER_39]: If by who, sorry?

574
00:48:20,474 --> 00:48:20,935
[SPEAKER_39]: Exactly.

575
00:48:21,255 --> 00:48:24,062
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, look, people said in 2014... Did anybody say promise?

576
00:48:24,783 --> 00:48:25,585
[SPEAKER_25]: Not to my knowledge.

577
00:48:25,765 --> 00:48:27,730
[SPEAKER_25]: No, but Boris Johnson keeps repeating it.

578
00:48:27,950 --> 00:48:29,634
[SPEAKER_25]: OK. Jeremy Corbyn keeps repeating it.

579
00:48:29,654 --> 00:48:30,536
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, we hear you.

580
00:48:30,877 --> 00:48:32,380
[SPEAKER_44]: I think you've had your answer.

581
00:48:32,400 --> 00:48:33,783
[SPEAKER_44]: Let's hear from a few more people in the audience.

582
00:48:33,803 --> 00:48:35,106
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, the woman there with the glasses.

583
00:48:35,086 --> 00:48:54,056
[SPEAKER_61]: So, in terms of the fact that Scotland needs to reduce its deficit in order to be allowed into the EU, does it therefore not make sense that independence wouldn't be a priority and Jeremy Corbyn's policies of putting more business and more infrastructure into Scotland should happen first so that you then can get into the EU?

584
00:48:54,516 --> 00:48:56,299
[SPEAKER_44]: Do you mind if I take a couple more points?

585
00:48:56,780 --> 00:48:59,524
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, the man here sitting right by me, I can't miss you.

586
00:48:59,504 --> 00:48:59,945
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

587
00:49:00,486 --> 00:49:05,636
[SPEAKER_06]: Nicola, our grandparents fought and died to protect Britain and the United Kingdom.

588
00:49:06,277 --> 00:49:12,830
[SPEAKER_06]: How would you explain to them your desire to break up this country?

589
00:49:12,850 --> 00:49:13,952
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, if you'd answer those two, please.

590
00:49:14,877 --> 00:49:23,332
[SPEAKER_39]: Firstly, on the point of EU membership, Scotland, whether we're in or out of the EU, wants to get its deficit down to sustainable levels.

591
00:49:23,432 --> 00:49:28,320
[SPEAKER_39]: Most countries across the Western world have deficits and we've set out plans to reduce that.

592
00:49:28,480 --> 00:49:29,442
[SPEAKER_39]: It is reducing already.

593
00:49:29,462 --> 00:49:34,050
[SPEAKER_39]: It's not a condition of joining the EU to meet those deficit levels.

594
00:49:34,030 --> 00:49:43,360
[SPEAKER_39]: I want to see more investment in Scotland from whoever is in government in Westminster, which is why I've set out the policies that the SNP would want to see pursued.

595
00:49:43,420 --> 00:49:49,286
[SPEAKER_39]: But our experience of Westminster governments over a long time is that that investment doesn't always come.

596
00:49:49,406 --> 00:50:00,358
[SPEAKER_39]: It's always also the case that if you want in Scotland to deprive Boris Johnson of a majority, then the way to do that is to vote SNP, because we're the main challengers in every Conservative seat.

597
00:50:00,338 --> 00:50:04,483
[SPEAKER_39]: On the issue of our grandparents, my grandmother was from the north of England.

598
00:50:05,864 --> 00:50:07,987
[SPEAKER_39]: I've got many family members in England.

599
00:50:08,888 --> 00:50:13,052
[SPEAKER_39]: I believe in independence so that Scotland can be self-governing.

600
00:50:13,353 --> 00:50:21,682
[SPEAKER_39]: But the closest ties of family, of history, social ties between Scotland, England, Wales, Northern Ireland, will always be close.

601
00:50:21,722 --> 00:50:25,546
[SPEAKER_39]: And I don't believe independence for Scotland is turning our backs on that.

602
00:50:25,626 --> 00:50:27,949
[SPEAKER_39]: It's simply making sure that Scotland

603
00:50:27,929 --> 00:50:31,115
[SPEAKER_39]: is in those relationships on the basis of equality.

604
00:50:31,135 --> 00:50:33,740
[SPEAKER_39]: And I think that's a good and positive thing for Scotland.

605
00:50:33,780 --> 00:50:36,666
[SPEAKER_39]: And actually, I think it would have benefits for the rest of the UK as well.

606
00:50:37,187 --> 00:50:40,774
[SPEAKER_39]: Let's take a question now from Stephen Whitelaw.

607
00:50:41,648 --> 00:50:50,664
[SPEAKER_62]: First Minister, on domestic matters, last year there was over 1,800 drug-related deaths in Scotland, the highest in Europe.

608
00:50:50,684 --> 00:50:54,711
[SPEAKER_62]: We are three times more likely to have a drug death in Scotland than elsewhere in England and Wales.

609
00:50:55,232 --> 00:50:58,037
[SPEAKER_62]: What are you doing about it and what needs to be done to reverse this trend?

610
00:50:58,270 --> 00:50:59,632
[SPEAKER_39]: That's a very good question.

611
00:51:00,212 --> 00:51:03,696
[SPEAKER_39]: Firstly, some context for that, as you're probably aware.

612
00:51:04,377 --> 00:51:18,392
[SPEAKER_39]: Scotland, because of our disproportionately high drug use back in the 1980s, there's an ageing cohort of drug users that have other health conditions, which is one, it's not the only reason, but it's one of the reasons for that rising number of drugs deaths.

613
00:51:18,793 --> 00:51:20,475
[SPEAKER_39]: It's a public health emergency.

614
00:51:20,495 --> 00:51:21,536
[SPEAKER_39]: It's not acceptable.

615
00:51:21,776 --> 00:51:26,121
[SPEAKER_39]: What we are doing about it, we're investing more money in drug treatment services.

616
00:51:26,161 --> 00:51:27,062
[SPEAKER_39]: We've established a

617
00:51:27,042 --> 00:51:35,603
[SPEAKER_39]: a task force made up of experts but also people with lived experience of drug use to look at the different, more innovative things that we need to do.

618
00:51:35,643 --> 00:51:40,575
[SPEAKER_39]: Power over the classification of drugs is still held at Westminster.

619
00:51:40,656 --> 00:51:43,262
[SPEAKER_39]: One of the things that Glasgow City Council

620
00:51:43,242 --> 00:51:55,220
[SPEAKER_39]: is wanting to do, and we are seeking the power in order to do that, is to establish in Glasgow what's called a safe consumption room, so that we can try to reduce some of the harm related to drugs.

621
00:51:55,240 --> 00:52:00,507
[SPEAKER_39]: But this is one of the most important issues that we're facing in Scotland, and I think there is a real...

622
00:52:00,527 --> 00:52:05,014
[SPEAKER_39]: I know there is a real determination, but I think it exists across parties to do absolutely that.

623
00:52:05,652 --> 00:52:10,318
[SPEAKER_62]: figures now indicate that on trend to actually be higher this year.

624
00:52:10,719 --> 00:52:13,583
[SPEAKER_62]: I think there's 500 odd drug deaths this year to date in relation to it.

625
00:52:14,284 --> 00:52:15,665
[SPEAKER_62]: So is the policies working just now?

626
00:52:16,687 --> 00:52:18,149
[SPEAKER_39]: There is more to do.

627
00:52:18,309 --> 00:52:24,157
[SPEAKER_39]: So some of these policies will be starting to have an effect, but it will take longer in some respects.

628
00:52:24,197 --> 00:52:32,849
[SPEAKER_39]: So I'm not going to stand here and make promises that I can't necessarily deliver in the year timescale that you're talking about.

629
00:52:32,869 --> 00:52:33,870
[SPEAKER_39]: What I can say

630
00:52:33,850 --> 00:52:41,982
[SPEAKER_39]: with absolute conviction is that there is a real determination to tackle this and to do what is required over whatever period is required.

631
00:52:42,283 --> 00:52:51,917
[SPEAKER_39]: I don't want, not just to be First Minister of a country, I don't want to be a citizen of a country in which we've got people dying unnecessarily of drug use.

632
00:52:52,318 --> 00:52:57,225
[SPEAKER_39]: If you take alcohol misuse, for example, which is not the same, we've

633
00:52:57,205 --> 00:52:59,549
[SPEAKER_39]: implemented, for example, minimum unit pricing.

634
00:52:59,809 --> 00:53:06,761
[SPEAKER_39]: So we have a record as a country of doing really courageous things when it comes to public health and we have got to show that same determination here too.

635
00:53:07,342 --> 00:53:08,864
[SPEAKER_44]: Is Jess Booth here somewhere?

636
00:53:09,125 --> 00:53:09,606
[SPEAKER_44]: Is that you?

637
00:53:09,626 --> 00:53:13,552
[SPEAKER_44]: I know from the questions you submitted you have personal experience of this.

638
00:53:13,652 --> 00:53:14,013
[SPEAKER_37]: I do.

639
00:53:15,395 --> 00:53:16,738
[SPEAKER_37]: I am a recovering addict.

640
00:53:17,819 --> 00:53:21,846
[SPEAKER_37]: I had an issue with benzodiazepines and

641
00:53:21,826 --> 00:53:37,692
[SPEAKER_37]: In the report that the gentleman's referenced up there, you talk about older people who have been through drug-related things in the 80s and things like that, but actually one of the biggest contributors to the rise in deaths is around benzodiazepines and the amount that they are

642
00:53:38,262 --> 00:53:44,230
[SPEAKER_37]: just prescribed to people who are in alcohol withdrawals or who are suffering from anxiety, suffering from mental health.

643
00:53:44,250 --> 00:53:53,201
[SPEAKER_37]: And there seems to be a real lack of education around what these drugs can do to people and how quickly it can ruin your life.

644
00:53:53,461 --> 00:53:56,605
[SPEAKER_37]: I came to the brink of death on these drugs.

645
00:53:57,486 --> 00:54:00,671
[SPEAKER_37]: And I'm one of the lucky ones.

646
00:54:00,971 --> 00:54:08,100
[SPEAKER_37]: And I feel like it is a situation that's not only being not really looked at properly in Scotland, but also throughout the whole of the UK.

647
00:54:08,536 --> 00:54:10,218
[SPEAKER_39]: Yeah, no, I think that is absolutely right.

648
00:54:10,378 --> 00:54:15,344
[SPEAKER_39]: And...

649
00:54:16,265 --> 00:54:17,146
[SPEAKER_39]: APPLAUSE Given your...

650
00:54:17,626 --> 00:54:18,447
[SPEAKER_39]: Excuse me a second.

651
00:54:18,467 --> 00:54:34,886
[SPEAKER_39]: Given your experience, if you were willing, I would love to talk to you a bit more and perhaps put you in touch with some of the people within the Scottish Government that are working on this, because it's really important that we do listen to people who have experience so that we can learn from that and make sure that the policies we're taking forward properly reflect that.

652
00:54:34,906 --> 00:54:37,969
[SPEAKER_39]: So, if you are willing to leave your details there, I would love to follow that up.

653
00:54:39,822 --> 00:54:43,608
[SPEAKER_57]: Yes, the woman here.

654
00:54:43,728 --> 00:54:51,260
[SPEAKER_57]: If you were in a coalition government, what would you do to make sure that those outside London are better represented in Westminster, not just Scottish people?

655
00:54:52,141 --> 00:54:56,648
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, that's a very good... Can I just clarify, firstly, not to dodge the question, because I'll come on to it.

656
00:54:56,668 --> 00:55:00,554
[SPEAKER_39]: I don't envisage being in a coalition government with Labour.

657
00:55:00,854 --> 00:55:04,260
[SPEAKER_39]: I think it would be a less formal arrangement than that, if we're in that situation.

658
00:55:04,760 --> 00:55:06,403
[SPEAKER_39]: But, you know,

659
00:55:06,670 --> 00:55:15,923
[SPEAKER_39]: many of the areas of England suffer from much the same neglect as Scotland does and much the same contempt from Westminster as Scotland does.

660
00:55:15,963 --> 00:55:21,290
[SPEAKER_39]: So the SNP will always try to stand up for decentralisation from London.

661
00:55:21,491 --> 00:55:25,236
[SPEAKER_39]: Much of what we have been able to do because we have a Scottish Parliament

662
00:55:25,216 --> 00:55:35,610
[SPEAKER_39]: some of the policies that Labour are now promising in their UK manifesto, I think with more power, with more devolution to some of the regions of England, would be possible there as well.

663
00:55:35,670 --> 00:55:41,337
[SPEAKER_39]: So the SNP will always be a voice for decentralisation and more powers to be spread around.

664
00:55:41,357 --> 00:55:41,958
[SPEAKER_44]: So how much...

665
00:55:41,978 --> 00:55:52,792
[SPEAKER_44]: So if you were in some kind of agreement, confidence supply, whatever it might be, with a Labour minority government, should that come to pass, how much involvement do you see, then, from that question, the SNP having in affairs south of the border?

666
00:55:52,812 --> 00:55:53,974
[SPEAKER_44]: Do you see yourself

667
00:55:53,954 --> 00:55:58,960
[SPEAKER_44]: actually getting stuck in, in terms of the laws that are passed for the rest of the UK?

668
00:55:59,381 --> 00:56:00,762
[SPEAKER_39]: No, we would always respect...

669
00:56:00,782 --> 00:56:04,908
[SPEAKER_39]: So we are responsible in Scotland for health policy and education, for example.

670
00:56:04,948 --> 00:56:23,050
[SPEAKER_39]: I don't think it's right that we would seek to... You know, no more right than it would be for Westminster to dictate to Scotland that we would dictate health policy or education policy in England, except where that affects Scotland, because often the decisions that are taken around Westminster on the health service, for example, have implications for our budget.

671
00:56:23,030 --> 00:56:44,329
[SPEAKER_39]: and one of the big issues in the next Parliament potentially for the health service is trade deals and we all have to come together those of us who don't want our NHS sold off to make sure that that doesn't happen so we will seek to exercise influence of course in Scotland's interest but where it is appropriate in the interests of people right across the UK.

672
00:56:44,528 --> 00:56:46,392
[SPEAKER_23]: Hello.

673
00:56:46,412 --> 00:56:56,370
[SPEAKER_23]: You have talked about economics and the deficit, and I know Scotland relies a lot, because in order to have your freedom, you are going to need money to do this.

674
00:56:56,911 --> 00:57:05,828
[SPEAKER_23]: You mentioned resources, and the North Sea is one of these key areas that is often raised.

675
00:57:05,808 --> 00:57:20,847
[SPEAKER_23]: Is it not important to let go of that now, to strand those assets and grow the natural resources like wind and tidal that Scotland is doing so much and raise the money that way rather than the oil and gas industry?

676
00:57:20,827 --> 00:57:24,673
[SPEAKER_39]: In a word, you are right, I agree with the sentiment.

677
00:57:24,793 --> 00:57:36,793
[SPEAKER_39]: If we were to stop oil and gas production tomorrow, we would become

678
00:57:36,773 --> 00:57:40,579
[SPEAKER_39]: more dependent on imports, which would actually increase the carbon footprint.

679
00:57:40,599 --> 00:57:44,164
[SPEAKER_39]: So we've got to have a managed transition and a just transition.

680
00:57:44,484 --> 00:57:46,047
[SPEAKER_39]: That transition is underway.

681
00:57:46,307 --> 00:57:48,130
[SPEAKER_39]: Rightly so, we've got to accelerate it.

682
00:57:48,390 --> 00:57:54,259
[SPEAKER_39]: We've got a net zero target in Scotland, in law already, of net zero emissions by 2045.

683
00:57:54,299 --> 00:57:56,783
[SPEAKER_39]: That's five years ahead of the rest of the UK.

684
00:57:56,823 --> 00:58:01,009
[SPEAKER_39]: So we've got to power on with these things and we're absolutely focused on doing it.

685
00:58:01,225 --> 00:58:06,166
[SPEAKER_44]: Right, well, there's been quite a few questions, but we, for the moment, are out of time.

686
00:58:06,186 --> 00:58:08,375
[SPEAKER_44]: So, First Minister Nicola Sturgeon, thank you very much indeed.

687
00:58:08,395 --> 00:58:08,957
[SPEAKER_44]: Thank you.

688
00:58:18,404 --> 00:58:21,872
[SPEAKER_44]: Okay, so we are halfway through.

689
00:58:21,912 --> 00:58:23,777
[SPEAKER_44]: Two down, two to go.

690
00:58:23,817 --> 00:58:25,200
[SPEAKER_44]: Still got lots of energy?

691
00:58:25,240 --> 00:58:26,243
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes.

692
00:58:26,263 --> 00:58:27,004
[SPEAKER_44]: Oh, great.

693
00:58:27,024 --> 00:58:34,843
[SPEAKER_44]: Okay, so we're going to end with the Prime Minister, Boris Johnson, but first let's welcome the leader of the Liberal Democrats, Jo Swinson.

694
00:58:42,417 --> 00:58:44,545
[SPEAKER_44]: So welcome to this Leaders Question Time.

695
00:58:44,565 --> 00:58:46,732
[SPEAKER_44]: I'm going to make the same plea to you, you've probably heard it.

696
00:58:47,535 --> 00:58:49,603
[SPEAKER_44]: Same plea for brevity and relevance.

697
00:58:49,623 --> 00:58:50,807
[SPEAKER_44]: That's what we want, isn't it?

698
00:58:51,766 --> 00:58:57,333
[SPEAKER_44]: And if you've been watching, you'll know that the audience has a lot of questions and I'm sure you want to hear as much from them as possible.

699
00:58:57,774 --> 00:58:57,994
[SPEAKER_44]: Absolutely.

700
00:58:58,014 --> 00:58:59,115
[SPEAKER_44]: So, let's get stuck in.

701
00:58:59,135 --> 00:59:02,299
[SPEAKER_44]: So, our first question for you is from James McLaughlin.

702
00:59:02,740 --> 00:59:04,302
[SPEAKER_45]: Hiya, how you getting on?

703
00:59:04,322 --> 00:59:05,964
[SPEAKER_45]: Yeah, very well, thanks, James.

704
00:59:05,984 --> 00:59:13,774
[SPEAKER_45]: Do you regret starting off the campaign by saying that you could be PM and do you now agree how ridiculous that sounded?

705
00:59:19,593 --> 00:59:20,920
[SPEAKER_31]: But I've just started with the easy ones.

706
00:59:22,507 --> 00:59:24,095
[SPEAKER_31]: No, I don't regret it.

707
00:59:24,698 --> 00:59:25,924
[SPEAKER_31]: And I'll tell you why.

708
00:59:27,052 --> 00:59:32,801
[SPEAKER_31]: I think many of you might have watched that debate on Monday night between Boris Johnson and Jeremy Corbyn.

709
00:59:33,462 --> 00:59:44,179
[SPEAKER_31]: And I don't know how you felt about it, but when I watched that, I felt pretty dismayed with the thought that somehow that has to be the choice, that that's all that we get to choose between.

710
00:59:44,219 --> 00:59:51,270
[SPEAKER_31]: And I'm in the position of leading a political party that's standing in more than 600 seats at this election,

711
00:59:51,250 --> 00:59:56,777
[SPEAKER_31]: And I'm proud to say that you don't have to make a choice between Boris Johnson and Jeremy Corbyn.

712
00:59:57,158 --> 01:00:06,990
[SPEAKER_31]: There is a better alternative, because I truly believe that our country deserves a better and brighter future than what either of them is offering right now.

713
01:00:07,071 --> 01:00:12,938
[SPEAKER_31]: And I'm determined, in my role as Liberal Democrat leader, to do everything I possibly can to make that happen.

714
01:00:12,998 --> 01:00:15,081
[SPEAKER_44]: But are you still saying that you

715
01:00:15,061 --> 01:00:17,284
[SPEAKER_44]: could be Prime Minister, that's the heart of the question.

716
01:00:17,324 --> 01:00:29,099
[SPEAKER_31]: There's still three weeks left in this campaign and all I would say is to anybody that thinks that you can predict the outcome of the election in the middle of the campaign, ask Theresa May how that worked out last time round.

717
01:00:29,400 --> 01:00:33,726
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, but you would need a tsunami of seats, 314.

718
01:00:33,786 --> 01:00:38,672
[SPEAKER_44]: So to answer the gentleman's question, are you still saying that you could be Prime Minister?

719
01:00:38,652 --> 01:00:48,530
[SPEAKER_31]: I recognise that things have got much more challenging since Boris Johnson and Nigel Farage cooked up a deal to stitch up seats between them.

720
01:00:48,710 --> 01:00:55,362
[SPEAKER_31]: I get that it is a big ask, but I am absolutely fighting for every Liberal Democrat vote and for every Liberal Democrat seat.

721
01:00:55,342 --> 01:01:00,855
[SPEAKER_31]: And we do live in a world where sometimes strange things have happened in politics.

722
01:01:01,096 --> 01:01:03,743
[SPEAKER_31]: I didn't predict that Trump was going to become president.

723
01:01:03,903 --> 01:01:06,650
[SPEAKER_31]: I didn't think Jeremy Corbyn was going to become leader of the Labour Party.

724
01:01:06,950 --> 01:01:11,141
[SPEAKER_31]: So I think we've all made some predictions which have not turned out to come true.

725
01:01:11,782 --> 01:01:12,945
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, the woman in the red jacket.

726
01:01:13,955 --> 01:01:18,743
[SPEAKER_41]: talk about the Lib Dems as a viable alternative to Labour or the Tories.

727
01:01:19,544 --> 01:01:32,506
[SPEAKER_41]: I would just like to ask you, with 14 million UK citizens now living in poverty, do you regret consistently voting with the Conservatives in favour of harsh and uncaring benefit cuts?

728
01:01:32,827 --> 01:01:36,132
[SPEAKER_41]: And how does that put them as any kind of alternative to the Conservatives?

729
01:01:40,583 --> 01:01:43,566
[SPEAKER_31]: I mean, I absolutely recognise the issue that you're raising.

730
01:01:43,586 --> 01:01:50,512
[SPEAKER_31]: And the bottom line is that there are far, far too many people in our country living in poverty and life is too hard.

731
01:01:50,953 --> 01:01:52,854
[SPEAKER_31]: And we did not get everything right.

732
01:01:53,175 --> 01:01:54,856
[SPEAKER_44]: So should we just look at your voting record?

733
01:01:55,457 --> 01:01:57,739
[SPEAKER_44]: In government, you voted for the bedroom tax.

734
01:01:57,959 --> 01:02:05,666
[SPEAKER_44]: You frequently voted against raising benefits and frequently voted against paying higher benefits to people with illnesses or disabilities.

735
01:02:05,926 --> 01:02:07,688
[SPEAKER_31]: So as I was saying,

736
01:02:07,988 --> 01:02:09,150
[SPEAKER_31]: We didn't get everything right.

737
01:02:09,891 --> 01:02:15,699
[SPEAKER_31]: We also had plenty of fights with the Conservatives.

738
01:02:16,060 --> 01:02:19,144
[SPEAKER_31]: And we won some of those fights, and we lost some of those fights.

739
01:02:19,224 --> 01:02:25,193
[SPEAKER_31]: And I am sorry that we did not win more of those fights in coalition because of the reasons that you are outlining.

740
01:02:25,433 --> 01:02:28,758
[SPEAKER_31]: Now, we did stop the Conservatives cutting 12 billion more from welfare.

741
01:02:28,778 --> 01:02:34,907
[SPEAKER_31]: We did stop them bringing in the two-child cap, which they did, of course, when they were on their own in 2015.

742
01:02:34,887 --> 01:02:37,732
[SPEAKER_31]: But I absolutely think that we have lessons to learn from that.

743
01:02:38,032 --> 01:02:39,034
[SPEAKER_31]: I've learned those lessons.

744
01:02:39,074 --> 01:02:52,638
[SPEAKER_31]: And if you look at what we're setting out, we are identifying six billion extra to put into universal credit to make sure that you don't have that five-week wait, which is hurting so many people, so that we get rid of that two-child cap, that we get rid of the bedroom tax.

745
01:02:52,938 --> 01:02:54,261
[SPEAKER_31]: So I get it.

746
01:02:54,601 --> 01:02:55,583
[SPEAKER_31]: We got stuff wrong.

747
01:02:55,903 --> 01:02:59,730
[SPEAKER_31]: And we, in the future, going forward, are determined to get it right.

748
01:03:00,470 --> 01:03:01,331
[SPEAKER_41]: Does that satisfy you?

749
01:03:01,451 --> 01:03:02,032
[SPEAKER_41]: Not at all.

750
01:03:02,072 --> 01:03:03,695
[SPEAKER_41]: Not in the slightest bit.

751
01:03:03,715 --> 01:03:09,283
[SPEAKER_41]: You're still going to keep the universal credit, which everybody knows is not working at all.

752
01:03:09,303 --> 01:03:14,911
[SPEAKER_41]: The Labour Party has made it absolutely clear that they're going to get rid of universal credit, and quite right.

753
01:03:15,151 --> 01:03:30,173
[SPEAKER_41]: And I can't honestly say that I could ever trust, after what happened in Sheffield, and we know all about that in Sheffield, when the Lib Dems went into coalition with the Conservatives, how can we expect it to be believing anything you say on this issue?

754
01:03:36,127 --> 01:03:42,341
[SPEAKER_31]: I absolutely accept the way that you feel, and I might not be able to convince you on this, and I recognise that.

755
01:03:43,022 --> 01:03:48,074
[SPEAKER_31]: I do think that scrapping universal credit on its own isn't some kind of magic bullet.

756
01:03:48,094 --> 01:03:50,359
[SPEAKER_31]: We need to have a system that provides support to people.

757
01:03:50,719 --> 01:03:54,608
[SPEAKER_31]: I think the biggest problems with universal credit is the lack of money that's in it.

758
01:03:54,588 --> 01:04:01,680
[SPEAKER_31]: not the principle that you try to have a simpler benefit system instead of there being multiple different payments that creates more complexity.

759
01:04:01,940 --> 01:04:08,151
[SPEAKER_31]: So I think the principle of making it simpler is a good one, but it needs to have the money behind it, and that's what we're setting out to do.

760
01:04:08,772 --> 01:04:09,133
[SPEAKER_44]: Okay.

761
01:04:09,313 --> 01:04:11,156
[SPEAKER_44]: I want to do something slightly different.

762
01:04:11,176 --> 01:04:13,941
[SPEAKER_44]: I want to take two questions in a row from two named people.

763
01:04:13,961 --> 01:04:17,627
[SPEAKER_44]: So can I hear from Catherine Fox and then Sue Lenkovsky?

764
01:04:17,647 --> 01:04:19,971
[SPEAKER_44]: So Catherine, that's you over there, right.

765
01:04:20,727 --> 01:04:27,275
[SPEAKER_46]: Is revoking Article 50 confirming to 17.4 million people that you think we're stupid and didn't know what we were voting for?

766
01:04:30,920 --> 01:04:31,000
[SPEAKER_16]: Sue?

767
01:04:31,020 --> 01:04:32,341
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm a passionate Remainer.

768
01:04:34,524 --> 01:04:44,777
[SPEAKER_16]: But the Liberal Democrats standing on a manifesto to unilaterally cancel Brexit and the electoral pact has absolutely cost you my vote.

769
01:04:45,449 --> 01:04:49,074
[SPEAKER_16]: The Liberal Democratic Party title is now a misnomer.

770
01:04:49,735 --> 01:04:51,257
[SPEAKER_16]: How can you defend that decision?

771
01:04:53,841 --> 01:04:56,905
[SPEAKER_31]: So you've got an unhappy Lever and an unhappy Remainer.

772
01:04:57,326 --> 01:05:05,718
[SPEAKER_31]: OK. What I would say in terms of our policy, look, we are being very straightforward as a party that we want to stop Brexit.

773
01:05:05,738 --> 01:05:06,619
[SPEAKER_31]: You might agree with us.

774
01:05:07,000 --> 01:05:08,001
[SPEAKER_31]: You might disagree with us.

775
01:05:08,342 --> 01:05:12,328
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't think you could accuse us of not being upfront about wanting to stop Brexit.

776
01:05:12,348 --> 01:05:15,372
[SPEAKER_31]: We have been crystal clear about that from the very beginning.

777
01:05:15,706 --> 01:05:22,353
[SPEAKER_31]: Not for one second do I think that that means that you or anybody like you is stupid.

778
01:05:22,433 --> 01:05:24,356
[SPEAKER_31]: I think it means we disagree.

779
01:05:25,036 --> 01:05:31,103
[SPEAKER_31]: And I really want us to be in a situation in this country where we can disagree with each other, Catherine.

780
01:05:31,263 --> 01:05:33,085
[SPEAKER_31]: And that means that you want to leave.

781
01:05:33,566 --> 01:05:35,268
[SPEAKER_31]: And I don't think that makes you a bad person.

782
01:05:35,728 --> 01:05:37,090
[SPEAKER_31]: And I want to remain in the EU.

783
01:05:37,190 --> 01:05:39,112
[SPEAKER_31]: And I hope you think that doesn't make me a bad person.

784
01:05:39,132 --> 01:05:41,815
[SPEAKER_46]: You can disagree with me, but you lost.

785
01:05:41,795 --> 01:05:45,362
[SPEAKER_46]: You don't get to keep disagreeing, you don't get to change it because you lost.

786
01:05:45,442 --> 01:05:55,382
[SPEAKER_31]: Look, I haven't changed my view on whether I think we are better off in the European Union and watching what I have seen in the last three and a half years

787
01:05:55,514 --> 01:06:05,606
[SPEAKER_31]: watching in Parliament MPs who voted to leave, who want Brexit, unable to agree amongst themselves about what Brexit looks like.

788
01:06:06,007 --> 01:06:10,052
[SPEAKER_31]: So Theresa May proposes a Brexit that Boris Johnson doesn't think is Brexity enough.

789
01:06:10,472 --> 01:06:19,243
[SPEAKER_31]: Boris Johnson proposes a Brexit that first of all Nigel Farage says he can't handle, but then who knows what discussions they've had and what's been offered in order to get him on board.

790
01:06:19,223 --> 01:06:32,128
[SPEAKER_31]: If even those MPs who have been putting forward Brexit can't agree, I tell you, I genuinely don't have confidence that there is a majority in this country for any specific type of Brexit.

791
01:06:32,148 --> 01:06:41,586
[SPEAKER_31]: And when the government analysis says that Brexit will make our country poorer and it will mean people lose their jobs and there is less money for our NHS,

792
01:06:41,566 --> 01:06:49,898
[SPEAKER_31]: If we really don't think that there is a majority for any specific type of Brexit, I think it would be irresponsible to go ahead with that without at least checking.

793
01:06:49,958 --> 01:06:52,061
[SPEAKER_31]: So we've argued for a people's vote.

794
01:06:52,442 --> 01:06:58,030
[SPEAKER_31]: And in this election, we're saying if you vote Liberal Democrat and get a Lib Dem majority government, we will revoke Article 50.

795
01:06:58,070 --> 01:06:59,612
[SPEAKER_31]: And if you don't, we will argue for a people's vote.

796
01:06:59,632 --> 01:07:01,735
[SPEAKER_31]: So what do you say to your former Lib Dem voter here?

797
01:07:01,715 --> 01:07:09,026
[SPEAKER_16]: You're not saying we'll go back to the people, you are unilaterally saying revoke it.

798
01:07:09,046 --> 01:07:15,055
[SPEAKER_16]: That is undemocratic from somebody who wishes the last three and a half years had never happened.

799
01:07:15,095 --> 01:07:22,806
[SPEAKER_16]: There is no difference between the pair of us.

800
01:07:22,826 --> 01:07:26,271
[SPEAKER_31]: So, I suspect you want a people's vote.

801
01:07:26,825 --> 01:07:33,139
[SPEAKER_16]: That, to me, is the only way forward, recognising people who are strongly to leave.

802
01:07:33,439 --> 01:07:38,210
[SPEAKER_31]: So we have been leading the fight for a people's vote for three and a half years.

803
01:07:38,310 --> 01:07:39,031
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah, but you're not now.

804
01:07:39,132 --> 01:07:42,118
[SPEAKER_44]: You're now leading the vote for revoking Article 50.

805
01:07:42,258 --> 01:07:43,922
[SPEAKER_31]: 17 times.

806
01:07:43,902 --> 01:07:47,827
[SPEAKER_31]: in Parliament, we put down amendments to try to secure a people's vote.

807
01:07:48,468 --> 01:07:57,680
[SPEAKER_31]: If Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party had backed that with sincerity, then we might be having a people's vote right now instead of a general election.

808
01:07:57,700 --> 01:07:59,222
[SPEAKER_31]: But we are in a general election.

809
01:07:59,923 --> 01:08:01,886
[SPEAKER_31]: This is the essence of democracy.

810
01:08:01,946 --> 01:08:04,189
[SPEAKER_31]: I am standing here and telling you honestly

811
01:08:04,169 --> 01:08:12,041
[SPEAKER_31]: what I would do if I was elected as Prime Minister, I would revoke Article 50 and if you vote me into that position, I will do what I've said I will do.

812
01:08:12,061 --> 01:08:14,064
[SPEAKER_31]: And that's the essence of democracy.

813
01:08:14,865 --> 01:08:16,988
[SPEAKER_22]: There are two women in the front here, let's hear from both of you.

814
01:08:17,449 --> 01:08:23,578
[SPEAKER_22]: You said you made some mistakes when you were in coalition with the Tories, so can you confirm whether you would go into a coalition with them again?

815
01:08:24,098 --> 01:08:26,323
[SPEAKER_31]: Certainly not under Boris Johnson.

816
01:08:26,363 --> 01:08:30,091
[SPEAKER_31]: This Conservative Party is off with Nigel Farage.

817
01:08:30,973 --> 01:08:33,639
[SPEAKER_31]: Boris Johnson's been endorsed by Tommy Robinson.

818
01:08:33,980 --> 01:08:37,147
[SPEAKER_31]: I mean, my goodness, they are so far off the charts.

819
01:08:37,428 --> 01:08:38,150
[SPEAKER_31]: Absolutely not.

820
01:08:38,470 --> 01:08:40,555
[SPEAKER_44]: There's a woman at the back who's had her hand up for ages, yes.

821
01:08:41,952 --> 01:08:47,698
[SPEAKER_36]: Hi, so you've admitted that you've made some mistakes, and I'm a student, so we've been let down by the Lib Dems before.

822
01:08:48,238 --> 01:08:50,000
[SPEAKER_44]: Are you talking about tuition fees, by any chance?

823
01:08:50,020 --> 01:08:52,463
[SPEAKER_36]: Yeah, that's what I was getting at.

824
01:08:52,723 --> 01:09:05,496
[SPEAKER_36]: But you also kind of called out Boris and Nigel for making a deal, but the Lib Dems have been making PACs, and there's definitely been some misleading suggestions in their campaign, so I don't... What's different now?

825
01:09:05,536 --> 01:09:06,457
[SPEAKER_36]: Why can we trust you now?

826
01:09:06,517 --> 01:09:08,719
[SPEAKER_36]: What do you mean, misleading suggestions in their campaign?

827
01:09:08,986 --> 01:09:12,574
[SPEAKER_36]: There's been some claims made that they...

828
01:09:13,697 --> 01:09:26,286
[SPEAKER_44]: It was a slightly unfortunate bar chart, wasn't there, Miss Swinson, in the North East Tyneside literature which suggested that we just kind of forgot all about the Brexit and the Labour Party in that bar chart and misrepresented the success of the Lib Dems in it.

829
01:09:26,266 --> 01:09:30,675
[SPEAKER_31]: I haven't seen that particular one, and it may well be that there was a problem with it.

830
01:09:30,696 --> 01:09:32,620
[SPEAKER_31]: I think all bar charts should be properly labelled.

831
01:09:32,680 --> 01:09:34,965
[SPEAKER_31]: It should be clear what they are explaining.

832
01:09:35,426 --> 01:09:36,909
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm a bit of a data geek.

833
01:09:36,929 --> 01:09:37,811
[SPEAKER_31]: I do like a bar chart.

834
01:09:37,891 --> 01:09:39,354
[SPEAKER_31]: I will be fairly straightforward about that.

835
01:09:39,394 --> 01:09:40,477
[SPEAKER_31]: But they often need to be right, don't they?

836
01:09:40,497 --> 01:09:40,617
[SPEAKER_31]: Sorry?

837
01:09:40,697 --> 01:09:41,659
[SPEAKER_44]: They need to be right.

838
01:09:41,639 --> 01:09:42,741
[SPEAKER_31]: And that one wasn't.

839
01:09:43,001 --> 01:09:46,086
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah, they do need to be right and they need to be clear what it is representing.

840
01:09:46,126 --> 01:09:47,989
[SPEAKER_31]: I absolutely, absolutely take that point.

841
01:09:48,229 --> 01:09:57,364
[SPEAKER_31]: But I mean, on that wider issue of trust, look, we absolutely got it wrong on tuition fees and, you know, I do apologise that we got that wrong and that we did that.

842
01:09:58,125 --> 01:10:01,470
[SPEAKER_31]: What I think we have been doing in the last three and a half years

843
01:10:01,450 --> 01:10:05,835
[SPEAKER_31]: is standing really clearly as a pro-European, pro-Remain party.

844
01:10:06,355 --> 01:10:11,621
[SPEAKER_31]: And we've not wavered from that, we've absolutely set that out, and that is what is at the centre of our manifesto this time.

845
01:10:11,921 --> 01:10:14,824
[SPEAKER_31]: So you can see that we are sticking to our principles and what we believe in.

846
01:10:15,665 --> 01:10:24,094
[SPEAKER_44]: And do you think, just seeing the silence that that fell into, do you think that the policy of revoking Article 50 has backfired?

847
01:10:25,196 --> 01:10:30,141
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, do you know, it is what we would do if we win a majority.

848
01:10:30,712 --> 01:10:30,992
[SPEAKER_31]: Right?

849
01:10:31,393 --> 01:10:34,376
[SPEAKER_31]: I just think we have to level and be straightforward about it.

850
01:10:34,656 --> 01:10:36,157
[SPEAKER_31]: We are a pro-European party.

851
01:10:36,218 --> 01:10:37,319
[SPEAKER_31]: We always have been.

852
01:10:37,699 --> 01:10:44,646
[SPEAKER_31]: And if we fight an election on the basis of stopping Brexit and people give us a majority, don't be surprised if we then stop Brexit.

853
01:10:44,906 --> 01:10:47,889
[SPEAKER_31]: But as I say, we have led that campaign for a people's vote.

854
01:10:48,430 --> 01:10:54,876
[SPEAKER_31]: And we, with more Liberal Democrat MPs in the next Parliament, will campaign for a people's vote if we're not able to revoke.

855
01:10:55,577 --> 01:10:56,618
[SPEAKER_44]: Roman in the orange top.

856
01:10:56,935 --> 01:11:06,509
[SPEAKER_32]: And yeah, my question is, so if, for me, I'm a remainer, I voted to remain, I would like a people's vote.

857
01:11:07,010 --> 01:11:18,287
[SPEAKER_32]: But for me, the Liberal Democrats seem more interested in just arguing with rather than working in collaboration with other parties and other politicians.

858
01:11:18,927 --> 01:11:22,032
[SPEAKER_32]: So for me, I don't see the point.

859
01:11:22,602 --> 01:11:29,352
[SPEAKER_44]: Well, actually, why haven't you ruled out a coalition with Jeremy Corbyn, who, of course, was just standing here just a few moments ago?

860
01:11:29,412 --> 01:11:35,141
[SPEAKER_44]: When they had promised a second referendum, they are surely your best hope to remain.

861
01:11:36,422 --> 01:11:47,459
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, I mean, Jeremy Corbyn also stood here and said that he would be neutral in that referendum, so I don't think that we, and the millions of people who want to remain in this country, can trust Jeremy Corbyn on Brexit.

862
01:11:47,479 --> 01:11:51,765
[SPEAKER_31]: But the other exchange that you had, which I thought was a very powerful exchange,

863
01:11:51,897 --> 01:11:58,911
[SPEAKER_31]: was about what's happened in the Labour Party under Jeremy Corbyn in terms of anti-Semitism, that they are being investigated by the Equality and Human Rights Commission.

864
01:11:59,171 --> 01:12:00,634
[SPEAKER_31]: And he said he was happy about that.

865
01:12:01,095 --> 01:12:03,199
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't think a party leader should be happy about that.

866
01:12:03,219 --> 01:12:04,762
[SPEAKER_31]: I think you should be ashamed about that.

867
01:12:05,123 --> 01:12:10,834
[SPEAKER_31]: And I just don't think that we can ignore the genuine fear that

868
01:12:10,814 --> 01:12:14,620
[SPEAKER_31]: lots of people feel about Jeremy Corbyn being Prime Minister.

869
01:12:15,041 --> 01:12:18,347
[SPEAKER_31]: So when it comes to working collaboratively, absolutely.

870
01:12:18,747 --> 01:12:19,929
[SPEAKER_31]: And what does that mean?

871
01:12:20,490 --> 01:12:24,897
[SPEAKER_31]: Let's just look at what we've done over the last couple of years, right?

872
01:12:25,318 --> 01:12:27,642
[SPEAKER_31]: We are here, it is November.

873
01:12:27,622 --> 01:12:29,945
[SPEAKER_31]: we are still members of the European Union.

874
01:12:30,606 --> 01:12:44,483
[SPEAKER_31]: And we were supposed to leave on the 29th of March, and we were supposed to leave on the 31st of October, and for people that wanted to leave, if that was you, then I appreciate you're going to be frustrated by that, but as a party that wanted to stop Brexit, we have worked collaboratively to make that happen.

875
01:12:44,503 --> 01:12:49,449
[SPEAKER_31]: We've worked with people in the Labour Party, in the Conservative Party, in the SNP, in Plaid Cymru and the Greens.

876
01:12:49,789 --> 01:12:54,675
[SPEAKER_31]: We have worked week in, week out, and we have stopped Brexit twice

877
01:12:54,655 --> 01:13:00,669
[SPEAKER_31]: Just imagine if you elect more Liberal Democrat MPs what we will be able to achieve and we'll be able to stop Brexit for good.

878
01:13:00,689 --> 01:13:01,591
[SPEAKER_44]: There's a forest of hands.

879
01:13:01,611 --> 01:13:04,357
[SPEAKER_44]: I'm going to go around a few people at once if that's all right by you.

880
01:13:04,377 --> 01:13:05,560
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, the woman here in the black top.

881
01:13:06,434 --> 01:13:21,151
[SPEAKER_53]: You talk a lot about working collaboratively with other parties, but your policy, in the unlikely event that you were elected Prime Minister with a majority, your policy of revoking Article 50 is just as divisive as the policies that are coming out from the hard Brexiteers.

882
01:13:21,531 --> 01:13:30,501
[SPEAKER_53]: How would you possibly imagine that you would be able to bring the country together if you were elected and you revoked Article 50?

883
01:13:30,481 --> 01:13:32,647
[SPEAKER_53]: the views of all those people that voted to leave.

884
01:13:32,667 --> 01:13:38,244
[SPEAKER_53]: I'm a Remain voter, but I come from a constituency, Rother Valley, that voted strongly to leave.

885
01:13:38,766 --> 01:13:42,818
[SPEAKER_53]: How would you bring communities like that together under your government?

886
01:13:42,878 --> 01:13:44,001
[SPEAKER_44]: The man here in the blue shirt.

887
01:13:45,044 --> 01:13:46,066
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, you.

888
01:13:46,386 --> 01:13:51,836
[SPEAKER_03]: I hear you talk about concern for the poor, but the reason people are poor is because of austerity, which you supported.

889
01:13:52,457 --> 01:13:59,931
[SPEAKER_03]: Your deputy leader recently said that he wants the government to run a permanent surplus, which is essentially a more palatable way of saying permanent austerity.

890
01:14:00,372 --> 01:14:03,257
[SPEAKER_03]: Why should we trust you not to further cripple our public services?

891
01:14:03,778 --> 01:14:04,960
[SPEAKER_44]: And the man there in the grey shirt.

892
01:14:06,880 --> 01:14:11,684
[SPEAKER_28]: We've apologised to students for the student debt debacle.

893
01:14:12,205 --> 01:14:13,666
[SPEAKER_28]: We haven't said what you're going to do for them.

894
01:14:14,046 --> 01:14:16,268
[SPEAKER_28]: So students are leaving with 50 grand worth of debt.

895
01:14:16,308 --> 01:14:20,552
[SPEAKER_28]: They're paying interest from the time they start to study when they can't possibly pay it back.

896
01:14:21,033 --> 01:14:24,636
[SPEAKER_28]: They're paying over 6% in interest when they're lucky enough to get a job.

897
01:14:24,976 --> 01:14:29,681
[SPEAKER_28]: We've created a generation of graduates who are in persistent debt to the state.

898
01:14:30,341 --> 01:14:32,403
[SPEAKER_28]: It just doesn't hang true.

899
01:14:32,703 --> 01:14:34,105
[SPEAKER_28]: So what are you going to do for those people?

900
01:14:34,385 --> 01:14:36,887
[SPEAKER_28]: We've created a whole generation in persistent debt.

901
01:14:36,867 --> 01:14:42,634
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, so three completely different topics there.

902
01:14:42,654 --> 01:14:52,607
[SPEAKER_31]: So, I absolutely recognise that so many people feel that this division that we have in our country right now is really horrible, it's really uncomfortable, right?

903
01:14:52,828 --> 01:15:02,520
[SPEAKER_31]: In this room, there's people who are Leave, Remain and so on, and I'm sure we all feel uncomfortable about that, and we kind of crave for and long for a feeling where that isn't there.

904
01:15:02,500 --> 01:15:05,104
[SPEAKER_31]: All I would say is I don't think there's an easy answer to this.

905
01:15:05,925 --> 01:15:16,861
[SPEAKER_31]: In Scotland, we've been living with this now for eight years because of the run-up to the independence referendum, and the society is still very divided on those lines.

906
01:15:16,881 --> 01:15:25,774
[SPEAKER_31]: So I don't think there's a quick fix, but I do think that many of the issues which people are unhappy about, that things don't...

907
01:15:25,754 --> 01:15:29,502
[SPEAKER_31]: things are too tough, that, you know, the economy doesn't work well enough for people.

908
01:15:30,204 --> 01:15:34,152
[SPEAKER_31]: I genuinely fear that those are going to be made worse by leaving the European Union.

909
01:15:34,172 --> 01:15:35,615
[SPEAKER_31]: There's going to be less money about it.

910
01:15:35,635 --> 01:15:42,931
[SPEAKER_31]: I mean, to take up the point about austerity, you know... Because what this questioner is saying is that you will make austerity worse by running a budget surplus.

911
01:15:43,071 --> 01:15:45,737
[SPEAKER_31]: But what my point is, is that...

912
01:15:45,717 --> 01:16:06,567
[SPEAKER_31]: it's leaving the European Union that is going to unleash austerity on our country because we are going to be poorer, people are going to lose their jobs, there will be less money for our NHS and it will be worse, whereas if we remain then we will actually have more money to spend to be able to invest in our communities and in resolving many of the issues that people are unhappy about.

913
01:16:06,647 --> 01:16:15,640
[SPEAKER_31]: So, you know, that's why I'm standing on that platform to say I want things to be better in our country because I recognise that for too many people it has been

914
01:16:15,620 --> 01:16:20,810
[SPEAKER_31]: I think that's a really good point.

915
01:16:20,971 --> 01:16:25,600
[SPEAKER_31]: I think that's a really good point.

916
01:16:25,700 --> 01:16:34,017
[SPEAKER_31]: I think that's a really good point.

917
01:16:33,997 --> 01:16:38,462
[SPEAKER_31]: But I'm not going to stand here and promise that we're going to abolish tuition fees.

918
01:16:38,482 --> 01:16:43,147
[SPEAKER_31]: There's a lot of numbers that are getting thrown around by different parties in this election.

919
01:16:43,567 --> 01:16:47,471
[SPEAKER_31]: And a lot of the stuff sounds good, but can it actually be delivered?

920
01:16:47,511 --> 01:16:56,561
[SPEAKER_31]: Do you actually, in your heart of hearts, believe that those sums add up when the IFS says that it's just not credible when you look at the Labour manifesto?

921
01:16:56,861 --> 01:17:00,865
[SPEAKER_31]: So I'd rather be straightforward and honest with people.

922
01:17:00,845 --> 01:17:04,670
[SPEAKER_28]: I think they should pay something, but I just think the balance is totally out of sync.

923
01:17:04,690 --> 01:17:05,911
[SPEAKER_28]: We need to help these people.

924
01:17:06,432 --> 01:17:09,836
[SPEAKER_28]: It's not about not paying anything, as the Labour government are suggesting.

925
01:17:10,276 --> 01:17:11,538
[SPEAKER_28]: There needs to be a rebalance.

926
01:17:11,578 --> 01:17:13,320
[SPEAKER_28]: So what is that rebalance?

927
01:17:13,340 --> 01:17:20,288
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah, and I think we need to look at how we invest in supporting particularly people from low incomes going into university to get more people doing that.

928
01:17:20,528 --> 01:17:24,473
[SPEAKER_31]: But if we really want to improve life chances,

929
01:17:24,453 --> 01:17:41,246
[SPEAKER_31]: the best place to put that money is in the early years and in schools, that's how you get that social mobility, that's how you give young people opportunities and that's where the priority for our spending is going, it's to make sure that we give our schools the money they need.

930
01:17:41,286 --> 01:17:44,132
[SPEAKER_31]: I mean at the moment in schools, right, you've got

931
01:17:44,112 --> 01:17:52,490
[SPEAKER_31]: teachers being sacked, you've got some schools not opening all day on a Friday, you've got schools crowdfunding for print sticks and exercise books.

932
01:17:52,510 --> 01:17:56,118
[SPEAKER_31]: I mean, if that doesn't tell you that our schools are in dire need of more funding, what does?

933
01:17:56,459 --> 01:17:59,205
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, let's take a question from Aldous Everard.

934
01:17:59,887 --> 01:18:01,831
[SPEAKER_44]: Whereabouts are you?

935
01:18:02,853 --> 01:18:03,775
[SPEAKER_44]: Ah, there you are.

936
01:18:04,244 --> 01:18:05,746
[SPEAKER_50]: Hi.

937
01:18:06,788 --> 01:18:13,738
[SPEAKER_50]: I'm sure that the Liberal Democrats feel as if you must feel like you're in a bit between a rock and a hard place at the moment.

938
01:18:15,040 --> 01:18:27,518
[SPEAKER_50]: But I'm just wondering, would your conscience be clear if, as a result of dividing the Remain vote,

939
01:18:27,616 --> 01:18:36,510
[SPEAKER_50]: between Labour, semi-Remain, I know, but we've got that next referendum with them.

940
01:18:37,832 --> 01:18:44,022
[SPEAKER_50]: If you divide that Remain vote, will your conscience be clear if the Tories manage to get a majority as a result of that?

941
01:18:50,228 --> 01:18:56,217
[SPEAKER_31]: If you vote for Boris Johnson, he will use that vote to put through his hard Brexit deal.

942
01:18:56,878 --> 01:19:01,644
[SPEAKER_31]: If you vote for Jeremy Corbyn, he will use that vote to negotiate a Labour Brexit deal.

943
01:19:02,105 --> 01:19:18,649
[SPEAKER_31]: In this election, my conscience would not be clear if I didn't make sure that right across the country, people have the chance to vote for a Remain party, for a candidate that wants to stop Brexit, because this might be the last chance that we have to stop it.

944
01:19:19,152 --> 01:19:21,260
[SPEAKER_50]: I fully agree.

945
01:19:21,420 --> 01:19:28,808
[SPEAKER_50]: I am a Remainer as well, but I don't want

946
01:19:29,412 --> 01:19:31,995
[SPEAKER_50]: this country not to go out of...

947
01:19:32,015 --> 01:19:37,141
[SPEAKER_50]: I would rather that we went out of Europe than we didn't have another referendum.

948
01:19:37,181 --> 01:19:48,374
[SPEAKER_50]: We need to have another referendum because we need to heal those wounds that have been caused by the initial referendum, which was so poorly worked out and which has been incredibly divisive for the country, for everyone.

949
01:19:48,994 --> 01:19:56,082
[SPEAKER_31]: And can I just say that, obviously, if there's more Liberal Democrats in that next Parliament, then that gives us more power to deliver that.

950
01:19:56,463 --> 01:19:58,525
[SPEAKER_31]: But we also need to make sure

951
01:19:59,298 --> 01:20:03,704
[SPEAKER_31]: to get there, that we stop Boris Johnson getting a majority.

952
01:20:04,205 --> 01:20:09,172
[SPEAKER_31]: And it's Liberal Democrats who are able to win seats from Boris Johnson and the Tories.

953
01:20:09,512 --> 01:20:12,096
[SPEAKER_31]: There's lots of places in the country where that can happen.

954
01:20:13,017 --> 01:20:17,864
[SPEAKER_31]: From what we're seeing, it's not the case that Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party are going to be able to win seats from the Conservatives.

955
01:20:18,284 --> 01:20:21,789
[SPEAKER_31]: And that's why voting Liberal Democrat is the way to deprive Boris Johnson of a majority.

956
01:20:22,430 --> 01:20:23,331
[SPEAKER_31]: The man in the red tie.

957
01:20:24,020 --> 01:20:37,501
[SPEAKER_11]: I've heard you this evening trying to defend your record on your vote and then on the other hand you'll say how you know you're against these horrible Tory cuts and I really really can't trust you and you got one difficult question and you immediately tried to turn it around to anti-semitism.

958
01:20:37,881 --> 01:20:46,635
[SPEAKER_11]: Jeremy Corbyn has been fighting anti-semitism and racism in all its forms since before you were born and you've got some brass neck to stand up there and call him an anti-semite.

959
01:20:50,817 --> 01:21:10,463
[SPEAKER_31]: I recognise that you genuinely believe that, but let me say, from the people that I've spoken to in the Labour Party, when I speak to Luciana Berger who joined the Liberal Democrats, when I speak to Louise Ellman who felt that she had to leave the Labour Party, and when I speak to Jewish people right across the country,

960
01:21:10,443 --> 01:21:11,364
[SPEAKER_31]: They do not feel.

961
01:21:11,844 --> 01:21:16,709
[SPEAKER_31]: They do not feel that Jeremy Corbyn is fighting racism and anti-Semitism in the Labour Party.

962
01:21:17,190 --> 01:21:18,992
[SPEAKER_31]: They know what that feels like.

963
01:21:19,092 --> 01:21:22,455
[SPEAKER_31]: And I'm going to listen to them and trust them on this issue.

964
01:21:22,936 --> 01:21:25,559
[SPEAKER_44]: Let's take a question now from Magdalene Lake.

965
01:21:26,419 --> 01:21:27,360
[SPEAKER_44]: Where's Magdalene?

966
01:21:27,380 --> 01:21:29,923
[SPEAKER_44]: Oh, there you are.

967
01:21:29,943 --> 01:21:36,670
[SPEAKER_55]: Having voted a number of times for fracking, how can we be sure of your commitment to halting climate change?

968
01:21:37,358 --> 01:21:39,423
[SPEAKER_31]: Well, and against fracking.

969
01:21:39,683 --> 01:21:42,771
[SPEAKER_31]: So why did you vote against a ban on it in 2015?

970
01:21:43,893 --> 01:21:54,338
[SPEAKER_31]: So, when we were in the coalition government, my Liberal Democrat colleague Ed Davey was the Energy Secretary and he put in place very stringent regulation.

971
01:21:54,318 --> 01:21:55,760
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, you're a deputy now, of course.

972
01:21:56,041 --> 01:21:56,301
[SPEAKER_31]: Indeed.

973
01:21:57,663 --> 01:22:00,007
[SPEAKER_31]: But as a party, things have moved on.

974
01:22:00,348 --> 01:22:01,189
[SPEAKER_31]: That was four years ago.

975
01:22:01,610 --> 01:22:02,892
[SPEAKER_31]: We are against fracking.

976
01:22:02,952 --> 01:22:12,327
[SPEAKER_31]: We want a ban on fracking because the climate emergency is such that we shouldn't be starting new fossil fuel industries.

977
01:22:12,543 --> 01:22:18,472
[SPEAKER_31]: We need to be changing the way that we produce our energy, the way that we heat our homes.

978
01:22:18,512 --> 01:22:22,578
[SPEAKER_31]: We need to be getting the carbon out of our everyday lives rapidly.

979
01:22:22,718 --> 01:22:26,343
[SPEAKER_31]: And that means no new fossil fuel industries such as fracking.

980
01:22:26,504 --> 01:22:30,970
[SPEAKER_44]: So you won't change your mind again, given that you voted against it, a ban on it in 2015.

981
01:22:30,990 --> 01:22:33,534
[SPEAKER_44]: You're now saying that you do think it should be banned.

982
01:22:33,554 --> 01:22:34,676
[SPEAKER_44]: You're not going to change your mind again.

983
01:22:34,716 --> 01:22:35,377
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm very clear.

984
01:22:35,437 --> 01:22:37,740
[SPEAKER_31]: We would ban fracking.

985
01:22:38,530 --> 01:22:40,774
[SPEAKER_55]: This is like all the other policies that you have.

986
01:22:41,255 --> 01:22:46,946
[SPEAKER_55]: They're Labour policies, and you are going on the back of what Labour are doing.

987
01:22:47,267 --> 01:22:54,801
[SPEAKER_55]: You say that you'll do progressive policies, like childcare and Sure Start and all that kind of stuff.

988
01:22:54,781 --> 01:22:56,104
[SPEAKER_55]: But you voted against it.

989
01:22:56,144 --> 01:22:59,791
[SPEAKER_55]: You voted against it when you were in Tory government.

990
01:23:00,152 --> 01:23:05,082
[SPEAKER_55]: You particularly, you yourself, have voted against progressive politics.

991
01:23:05,463 --> 01:23:08,970
[SPEAKER_55]: And every time you are asked about something, you attack Labour.

992
01:23:09,431 --> 01:23:10,714
[SPEAKER_55]: And you pretend to be

993
01:23:10,694 --> 01:23:15,584
[SPEAKER_55]: somebody who is akin to Labour in some of those progressive policies.

994
01:23:15,624 --> 01:23:16,746
[SPEAKER_55]: Well, I don't believe it.

995
01:23:16,907 --> 01:23:20,033
[SPEAKER_55]: I don't think that you have progressive policies.

996
01:23:20,594 --> 01:23:23,059
[SPEAKER_55]: I don't think that you have left-wing policies.

997
01:23:23,400 --> 01:23:30,154
[SPEAKER_55]: I think that actually the Liberal Democrats are right-wing party and they do not get my vote.

998
01:23:37,137 --> 01:23:47,852
[SPEAKER_31]: And if you support the Labour Party and if you want socialism and that's your viewpoint, then we're not a socialist party.

999
01:23:48,313 --> 01:23:48,974
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm a liberal.

1000
01:23:49,395 --> 01:23:54,522
[SPEAKER_31]: And it's not some annex to the Labour Party.

1001
01:23:54,502 --> 01:23:55,643
[SPEAKER_31]: a liberal party.

1002
01:23:55,723 --> 01:23:59,246
[SPEAKER_31]: We want an open and a fair and inclusive country.

1003
01:23:59,286 --> 01:24:00,807
[SPEAKER_31]: We're an internationalist party.

1004
01:24:00,848 --> 01:24:10,356
[SPEAKER_31]: That's why we want to remain in the European Union and stop Brexit, because we believe that you get further, you achieve more if you work with your closest neighbours.

1005
01:24:10,756 --> 01:24:12,177
[SPEAKER_31]: That's what we are standing for.

1006
01:24:12,217 --> 01:24:13,218
[SPEAKER_31]: That's what our values are.

1007
01:24:13,258 --> 01:24:18,223
[SPEAKER_31]: And sometimes we do agree with the Labour Party, but we are not the Labour Party.

1008
01:24:18,263 --> 01:24:19,524
[SPEAKER_31]: We are a different party.

1009
01:24:19,604 --> 01:24:21,766
[SPEAKER_31]: And that's why we're standing separately.

1010
01:24:21,866 --> 01:24:24,508
[SPEAKER_31]: We stand on our own two feet in this election.

1011
01:24:24,488 --> 01:24:26,090
[SPEAKER_31]: The woman right at the back there.

1012
01:24:26,971 --> 01:24:27,372
[SPEAKER_00]: Hiya.

1013
01:24:27,772 --> 01:24:34,782
[SPEAKER_00]: I just kind of want to follow up about the whole climate change because recently on this week you said you would be OK with using nuclear weapons.

1014
01:24:35,002 --> 01:24:38,947
[SPEAKER_00]: Can you please clarify why you think that would be OK and how is that going to protect the planet?

1015
01:24:46,457 --> 01:24:46,918
[SPEAKER_31]: APPLAUSE So...

1016
01:24:47,658 --> 01:24:49,240
[SPEAKER_31]: We live in a really dangerous world.

1017
01:24:49,701 --> 01:25:05,785
[SPEAKER_31]: I think it feels like it is a much more uncertain world than even a few years ago, when you have President Trump in the White House with his volatile decisions in geopolitics.

1018
01:25:06,085 --> 01:25:11,500
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't think this is the time to get rid of our nuclear deterrent.

1019
01:25:11,821 --> 01:25:18,019
[SPEAKER_31]: I think that we need to keep our nuclear deterrent and that it keeps us safe.

1020
01:25:18,404 --> 01:25:26,115
[SPEAKER_31]: I do think the best use for nuclear weapons is to use them to negotiate away other nuclear weapons.

1021
01:25:26,435 --> 01:25:37,710
[SPEAKER_31]: And the UK should be playing a leading role in all of those international diplomatic discussions about how do we create a world without nuclear weapons, because that is what we want to see.

1022
01:25:37,991 --> 01:25:39,112
[SPEAKER_31]: But we are not there.

1023
01:25:39,573 --> 01:25:43,999
[SPEAKER_31]: And while we are not there, then I do not want us to scrap our deterrent.

1024
01:25:44,500 --> 01:25:45,441
[SPEAKER_31]: Merlin, the blue shirt.

1025
01:25:46,298 --> 01:25:48,942
[SPEAKER_34]: You seem to be the party of missed opportunity.

1026
01:25:49,002 --> 01:25:55,231
[SPEAKER_34]: When you were in coalition with the Conservatives, you failed to stop them doing a number of things you would now reverse.

1027
01:25:56,453 --> 01:26:03,784
[SPEAKER_34]: When the Conservatives were heavily in minority in government just recently, you failed to

1028
01:26:05,148 --> 01:26:14,338
[SPEAKER_34]: put your pride to one side, team up with Corbyn and the others, and bring down the government, and then bring forward a referendum.

1029
01:26:15,000 --> 01:26:15,983
[SPEAKER_34]: We don't have to have a selection.

1030
01:26:16,083 --> 01:26:17,267
[SPEAKER_34]: We could have avoided it.

1031
01:26:18,142 --> 01:26:20,948
[SPEAKER_31]: I have to disagree.

1032
01:26:21,329 --> 01:26:29,949
[SPEAKER_31]: Just a couple of weeks before this election was called, the Liberal Democrats tabled again an amendment to have a people's vote and the Labour Party refused to back it.

1033
01:26:30,189 --> 01:26:37,045
[SPEAKER_31]: We have been consistent in doing that and we did achieve more money for poorer pupils, we achieved same-sex marriage, we cut taxes,

1034
01:26:37,025 --> 01:26:38,527
[SPEAKER_31]: for people on low pay.

1035
01:26:38,587 --> 01:26:41,612
[SPEAKER_31]: We introduced shared parental leave and gender pay gap reporting.

1036
01:26:41,632 --> 01:26:53,871
[SPEAKER_31]: You know there was a whole host of things that we did achieve when we were in government and I always want us to do more and that's why I'm ambitious for our future because our country can have a brighter future and it starts with remaining in the European Union.

1037
01:26:54,132 --> 01:26:56,215
[SPEAKER_44]: Our time is up I'm afraid Miss Swinson.

1038
01:26:56,355 --> 01:26:57,377
[SPEAKER_44]: Thank you very much indeed.

1039
01:26:57,397 --> 01:26:59,320
[SPEAKER_44]: Would you please thank Jo Swinson.

1040
01:27:08,530 --> 01:27:10,217
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, are you still with us?

1041
01:27:10,257 --> 01:27:12,827
[SPEAKER_44]: Because it is now the last of our four leaders.

1042
01:27:12,907 --> 01:27:17,325
[SPEAKER_44]: Would you please welcome the leader of the Conservative Party and, of course, the Prime Minister, Boris Johnson.

1043
01:27:26,536 --> 01:27:30,121
[SPEAKER_44]: Right, so, if you've been watching the programme so far, I expect you have.

1044
01:27:30,201 --> 01:27:30,741
[SPEAKER_10]: Quite a lot of it.

1045
01:27:30,781 --> 01:27:44,379
[SPEAKER_44]: Wrapped with attention, you'll have heard me ask each leader to allow the audience time to ask as many questions as possible, so to keep your answers relevant and reasonably brief, and forgive me for interrupting you if you don't.

1046
01:27:45,060 --> 01:27:49,405
[SPEAKER_44]: So, let's take our first question for Mr Johnson, which is from Mae Rooks.

1047
01:27:50,144 --> 01:27:51,267
[SPEAKER_42]: Hello, Prime Minister.

1048
01:27:51,928 --> 01:27:57,200
[SPEAKER_42]: I'd just like to ask you, how important is it for someone in your position of power to always tell the truth?

1049
01:27:57,861 --> 01:28:01,369
[SPEAKER_13]: I think it's absolutely vital.

1050
01:28:03,087 --> 01:28:14,577
[SPEAKER_13]: I think it's absolutely vital, and I think that the issue of trust in politics is central to this election and fundamental to the corrosion of trust in politics at the moment.

1051
01:28:14,998 --> 01:28:16,959
[SPEAKER_13]: So why do you think you're being asked that question?

1052
01:28:16,979 --> 01:28:17,600
[SPEAKER_13]: Let's be clear.

1053
01:28:17,740 --> 01:28:21,964
[SPEAKER_13]: It's the failure of politicians to deliver Brexit.

1054
01:28:22,284 --> 01:28:23,725
[SPEAKER_13]: Because the people of the EU...

1055
01:28:23,805 --> 01:28:24,366
[SPEAKER_13]: Hang on.

1056
01:28:24,466 --> 01:28:25,367
[SPEAKER_13]: Hang on a minute.

1057
01:28:25,387 --> 01:28:28,049
[SPEAKER_44]: People were told 3.5 years ago... Just a minute, Prime Minister.

1058
01:28:28,069 --> 01:28:28,410
[SPEAKER_42]: I'm sorry.

1059
01:28:28,690 --> 01:28:29,370
[SPEAKER_42]: Is that what you meant?

1060
01:28:30,151 --> 01:28:32,233
[SPEAKER_42]: Erm...

1061
01:28:32,213 --> 01:28:39,886
[SPEAKER_42]: I'm speaking from a WASPs and you know who the WASPs are and you've made statements to help and take that forward.

1062
01:28:40,687 --> 01:28:45,054
[SPEAKER_42]: Are you still in that frame of mind that you're going to help us out?

1063
01:28:45,535 --> 01:28:47,438
[SPEAKER_42]: You're going to sort this pension issue?

1064
01:28:47,806 --> 01:28:58,402
[SPEAKER_13]: Well, the WASPI issue, as everybody knows, is a very difficult problem caused by a change in the pension age for women who retire at a certain age.

1065
01:28:58,543 --> 01:29:03,671
[SPEAKER_13]: And I do sympathise deeply with the position of the WASPI women.

1066
01:29:03,691 --> 01:29:05,453
[SPEAKER_13]: And we have looked at it and looked at it and looked at it.

1067
01:29:05,513 --> 01:29:08,378
[SPEAKER_13]: I would love to be able to magic you any solution.

1068
01:29:08,398 --> 01:29:09,780
[SPEAKER_13]: But are you going to take action apart from looking?

1069
01:29:09,760 --> 01:29:14,907
[SPEAKER_13]: It is very expensive to come up with the solution that you want.

1070
01:29:14,927 --> 01:29:17,530
[SPEAKER_13]: And I'm going to be honest with you tonight.

1071
01:29:17,710 --> 01:29:21,755
[SPEAKER_13]: I cannot promise that I can magic up that money for you tonight.

1072
01:29:21,996 --> 01:29:24,439
[SPEAKER_13]: All the demands that the WASP women make.

1073
01:29:24,899 --> 01:29:32,489
[SPEAKER_13]: We are going to look at it, but it is not possible to satisfy all the demands of the WASP women.

1074
01:29:32,569 --> 01:29:35,153
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm going to put my hands up and confess that.

1075
01:29:35,253 --> 01:29:36,294
[SPEAKER_44]: A few points, if I may.

1076
01:29:36,314 --> 01:29:36,975
[SPEAKER_44]: It's about three or four.

1077
01:29:36,995 --> 01:29:37,776
[SPEAKER_44]: Can we start with you?

1078
01:29:38,228 --> 01:29:40,331
[SPEAKER_54]: I think it's the most important point of this general election.

1079
01:29:40,431 --> 01:29:44,157
[SPEAKER_54]: Why are you refusing to release the report on Russian interference in British politics?

1080
01:29:44,237 --> 01:29:47,181
[SPEAKER_44]: Because...

1081
01:29:47,201 --> 01:29:48,583
[SPEAKER_44]: If I may, I'm going to take three or four points at a time.

1082
01:29:48,603 --> 01:29:49,865
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes.

1083
01:29:49,885 --> 01:29:53,370
[SPEAKER_63]: Why should you be Prime Minister if you constantly keep on avoiding scrutiny?

1084
01:29:53,410 --> 01:30:04,246
[SPEAKER_63]: You've cancelled Parliament for five weeks, you ran away from Channel 4's debate, which is meant to be this Sunday, and you've banned the Daily Mirror from the Conservative bus.

1085
01:30:05,027 --> 01:30:06,109
[SPEAKER_63]: The woman here in the blue dress.

1086
01:30:06,224 --> 01:30:13,962
[SPEAKER_35]: You keep saying that leave is the will of the people, but I don't think I've ever heard you address specific issues bringing into question the validity of the referendum.

1087
01:30:14,463 --> 01:30:18,974
[SPEAKER_35]: For example, we know that the Leave campaign broke electoral spending rules and privacy laws.

1088
01:30:19,495 --> 01:30:24,908
[SPEAKER_35]: We know that many people voted to leave based on wrong information, including what was written on the side of a bus.

1089
01:30:24,888 --> 01:30:48,432
[SPEAKER_35]: We know that leave was not defined and still isn't actually agreed upon today and I'd love for you to address these issues and also actually talk about why you think you've got a mandate to go through with Brexit because I don't think you can say that this general election can be your mandate when Brexit is mixed in with healthcare and climate change and education.

1090
01:30:48,682 --> 01:31:01,974
[SPEAKER_13]: I am very happy to be scrutinised.

1091
01:31:02,814 --> 01:31:12,783
[SPEAKER_13]: On your point about the reasons for having the election, let's be in no doubt, I did not want to have an election now and no Prime Minister wants to have an election on 12 December.

1092
01:31:13,544 --> 01:31:18,368
[SPEAKER_13]: We had to do it because Parliament is blocking Brexit.

1093
01:31:18,348 --> 01:31:18,788
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm afraid...

1094
01:31:19,049 --> 01:31:21,091
[SPEAKER_13]: Hang on, that's not quite right.

1095
01:31:21,311 --> 01:31:24,054
[SPEAKER_44]: Parliament voted to accept a reading of your bill.

1096
01:31:24,795 --> 01:31:26,697
[SPEAKER_44]: They then didn't want to do it in just three days.

1097
01:31:27,057 --> 01:31:30,101
[SPEAKER_13]: Well, they were given every opportunity to pass it.

1098
01:31:31,342 --> 01:31:39,371
[SPEAKER_13]: They were given every opportunity to pass it and they passed a law to insist that we extended beyond October the 31st.

1099
01:31:39,551 --> 01:31:43,495
[SPEAKER_13]: And what we have now is a situation in which the other three party leaders

1100
01:31:43,475 --> 01:31:51,403
[SPEAKER_13]: either want to block Brexit or absurdly want to have a second referendum on the EU without... And that's, I think, Mr Corbyn's position.

1101
01:31:51,463 --> 01:31:53,725
[SPEAKER_13]: It seems to have mutated tonight.

1102
01:31:54,245 --> 01:31:59,050
[SPEAKER_13]: He's now going to be neutral on the deal that he proposes to do.

1103
01:31:59,070 --> 01:32:04,235
[SPEAKER_13]: I don't see how he can do a deal when he's going to be neutral or indifferent about the deal that he wants to do.

1104
01:32:04,515 --> 01:32:05,276
[SPEAKER_13]: Never mind that.

1105
01:32:05,596 --> 01:32:08,619
[SPEAKER_13]: I do not think whatever deal Mr Corbyn proposes...

1106
01:32:08,639 --> 01:32:09,600
[SPEAKER_13]: I don't think it's sensible.

1107
01:32:09,580 --> 01:32:24,333
[SPEAKER_13]: for this great country of ours to spend next year in yet more delectable disputations about the EU, and then another referendum, if I understood correctly what happened earlier on, another referendum on Scotland.

1108
01:32:24,353 --> 01:32:26,095
[SPEAKER_13]: How can that be right for our country?

1109
01:32:26,355 --> 01:32:28,917
[SPEAKER_13]: I want next year to be a fantastic year for our country.

1110
01:32:29,158 --> 01:32:31,980
[SPEAKER_13]: We're a very ambitious, one-nation Conservative government.

1111
01:32:32,000 --> 01:32:39,587
[SPEAKER_13]: We have amazing plans for this country, investing in education, investing in health, and that's what we want to get on with, and we need to get Brexit done to do it.

1112
01:32:39,567 --> 01:32:40,909
[SPEAKER_44]: it.

1113
01:32:43,092 --> 01:32:45,376
[SPEAKER_44]: It took about three minutes to get that phrase in.

1114
01:32:48,280 --> 01:33:01,980
[SPEAKER_10]: Mr Johnson, whilst you claim the economy is doing really well, how can you justify, for example in my constituency where I work as a senior leader in a secondary school, how can you justify that 40%

1115
01:33:01,960 --> 01:33:04,645
[SPEAKER_10]: of the children in my community are living in poverty.

1116
01:33:05,226 --> 01:33:09,694
[SPEAKER_10]: And nationally, many, many more people are homeless.

1117
01:33:10,275 --> 01:33:15,645
[SPEAKER_10]: And many people who are working, perhaps on 40-hour contracts a week, are having to use food banks.

1118
01:33:15,665 --> 01:33:21,015
[SPEAKER_10]: So how can you justify this?

1119
01:33:22,261 --> 01:33:25,244
[SPEAKER_13]: whereabouts is your school?

1120
01:33:25,544 --> 01:33:30,429
[SPEAKER_10]: In Stannington, towards Hillsworth, Sheffield.

1121
01:33:30,589 --> 01:33:36,855
[SPEAKER_13]: I want you to know that I have been in office for about 120 days or so as Prime Minister.

1122
01:33:37,276 --> 01:33:43,161
[SPEAKER_13]: I do understand, I have been to many hospitals and many schools in the time I have been Prime Minister.

1123
01:33:43,181 --> 01:33:47,225
[SPEAKER_13]: I have talked to nurses and doctors and teachers about what is going on in their schools.

1124
01:33:47,305 --> 01:33:48,066
[SPEAKER_13]: That is why I

1125
01:33:48,046 --> 01:33:58,899
[SPEAKER_13]: We're now levelling up funding for education across this country, putting more money into both primary and secondary schools, and I want to see that going directly to your school.

1126
01:33:59,360 --> 01:34:01,202
[SPEAKER_13]: But I just make the crucial point...

1127
01:34:01,222 --> 01:34:03,385
[SPEAKER_44]: But Mr Johnson, this is a question about your record.

1128
01:34:03,405 --> 01:34:09,152
[SPEAKER_44]: You say you've been Prime Minister for about 120 days, which of course is true, but the Conservatives have been in power for nine years.

1129
01:34:09,172 --> 01:34:09,953
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes, absolutely.

1130
01:34:09,933 --> 01:34:15,006
[SPEAKER_13]: That is a fair point, Fiona.

1131
01:34:15,207 --> 01:34:19,237
[SPEAKER_13]: For most of that time, I was running London.

1132
01:34:20,220 --> 01:34:25,714
[SPEAKER_13]: When I was running London, we reduced the gap between rich and poor.

1133
01:34:25,694 --> 01:34:34,205
[SPEAKER_13]: and one of the things I did, which we have now brought into government, we introduced the Living Wage, we massively expanded the Living Wage when I was Mayor of London.

1134
01:34:34,486 --> 01:34:36,789
[SPEAKER_13]: That became a national policy.

1135
01:34:37,189 --> 01:34:43,498
[SPEAKER_13]: George Osborne nicked it from me, an act of theft, I was perfectly happy to condone, and it has become a national policy.

1136
01:34:43,518 --> 01:34:44,479
[SPEAKER_13]: I am proud to say

1137
01:34:44,459 --> 01:34:50,645
[SPEAKER_13]: that under us Conservatives, we're going to raise the living wage to its highest ever level.

1138
01:34:50,865 --> 01:34:55,150
[SPEAKER_13]: And I guess if you ask me, do I want to tackle poverty in your area?

1139
01:34:55,170 --> 01:34:56,351
[SPEAKER_13]: Yes, I certainly do.

1140
01:34:56,851 --> 01:35:02,597
[SPEAKER_13]: And yes, I certainly want to give every kid in the country the opportunities to make the most of their talents.

1141
01:35:02,617 --> 01:35:05,720
[SPEAKER_13]: And that is what I believe in passionately as a Conservative.

1142
01:35:05,740 --> 01:35:08,182
[SPEAKER_13]: I want to see equality of opportunity in this country.

1143
01:35:08,202 --> 01:35:13,808
[SPEAKER_13]: I believe that you have talent, genius, ability,

1144
01:35:13,788 --> 01:35:16,791
[SPEAKER_13]: uniformly distributed throughout the whole of the UK.

1145
01:35:17,132 --> 01:35:17,192
[SPEAKER_13]: OK.

1146
01:35:17,212 --> 01:35:19,194
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm going to get them on side with one like that, I don't think.

1147
01:35:19,434 --> 01:35:20,776
[SPEAKER_13]: To unleash that potential.

1148
01:35:20,796 --> 01:35:21,597
[SPEAKER_13]: OK. That's what I want to do.

1149
01:35:21,957 --> 01:35:23,118
[SPEAKER_44]: Let's hear from Sandeep.

1150
01:35:23,879 --> 01:35:25,781
[SPEAKER_44]: Sandeep Gill, whereabouts?

1151
01:35:25,841 --> 01:35:26,282
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes.

1152
01:35:26,642 --> 01:35:27,883
[SPEAKER_44]: Oh, there you are.

1153
01:35:27,903 --> 01:35:36,173
[SPEAKER_40]: Firstly, Mr Johnson, I'd like to say, whilst you're in South Yorkshire, I hope you managed to stay dry, unlike a lot of the residents in the past month.

1154
01:35:37,074 --> 01:35:37,534
[SPEAKER_40]: So...

1155
01:35:38,847 --> 01:35:48,892
[SPEAKER_40]: As a working single mother, I rely on benefits to get by and just about manage to sustain myself and my two children.

1156
01:35:49,995 --> 01:35:55,489
[SPEAKER_40]: Under the Conservative government, what guarantee do I have of staying on this side of the food banks?

1157
01:35:56,633 --> 01:36:09,569
[SPEAKER_13]: We will... First of all, about the flooding, I'm very, very determined to make sure that everybody whose lives have been affected by flooding gets the compensation and the help that they need.

1158
01:36:09,609 --> 01:36:18,000
[SPEAKER_13]: You've seen our announcement that every damaged home is going to get at least £5,000 to help them with repairs.

1159
01:36:18,217 --> 01:36:21,282
[SPEAKER_13]: in addition to what we're doing to help with council tax and other things.

1160
01:36:21,302 --> 01:36:23,565
[SPEAKER_13]: And we'll also help with insurance.

1161
01:36:23,865 --> 01:36:36,985
[SPEAKER_13]: But on your basic question about tackling poverty, of course we want to deal with not just the expression of poverty, but also with the causes of poverty.

1162
01:36:36,965 --> 01:36:40,429
[SPEAKER_13]: and that means dealing with educational standards.

1163
01:36:40,470 --> 01:36:50,262
[SPEAKER_13]: It means spreading ambition and hope around the country by investing in education, investing in social services, adult and child social services as we are now.

1164
01:36:50,743 --> 01:36:57,792
[SPEAKER_13]: Also, it's not just a question of the living wage, it's also a question of helping people with the cost of living.

1165
01:36:57,772 --> 01:37:12,333
[SPEAKER_13]: and that's why we're cutting national insurance contributions and trying to put more... doing things to help people with the cost of their heating, their fuel bills, and putting more money into people's pockets every year.

1166
01:37:12,373 --> 01:37:15,037
[SPEAKER_13]: We want to help people with the cost of living.

1167
01:37:15,057 --> 01:37:17,681
[SPEAKER_13]: How much is cutting those national insurance levels?

1168
01:37:17,701 --> 01:37:21,567
[SPEAKER_13]: How much is that going to save people every week?

1169
01:37:21,587 --> 01:37:23,610
[SPEAKER_44]: How much is that going to save people every week?

1170
01:37:23,590 --> 01:37:30,982
[SPEAKER_13]: I agree, it's only £100 a year to begin with.

1171
01:37:31,042 --> 01:37:31,784
[SPEAKER_44]: £100 a year?

1172
01:37:32,405 --> 01:37:34,608
[SPEAKER_13]: But it's £500 a year.

1173
01:37:34,749 --> 01:37:38,074
[SPEAKER_13]: It's £500 a year once we've got to our ambition.

1174
01:37:38,094 --> 01:37:39,557
[SPEAKER_44]: You say it's £500, but it's under £100.

1175
01:37:39,617 --> 01:37:41,219
[SPEAKER_13]: Once we've got to our ambition of £12,500.

1176
01:37:41,239 --> 01:37:44,605
[SPEAKER_13]: I want to do more to reduce the tax burden.

1177
01:37:45,306 --> 01:37:48,531
[SPEAKER_13]: Hang on, let's let Sandeep back in.

1178
01:37:48,632 --> 01:37:49,513
[SPEAKER_13]: Sorry, Sandeep.

1179
01:37:49,493 --> 01:37:55,286
[SPEAKER_40]: You're promising that, yet I'm yet to be moved on to universal credit.

1180
01:37:55,346 --> 01:37:56,148
[SPEAKER_40]: How does that work?

1181
01:37:56,208 --> 01:38:01,379
[SPEAKER_40]: I'm going to lose money, and yet you're promising more relief in other areas.

1182
01:38:01,439 --> 01:38:02,642
[SPEAKER_40]: It doesn't make sense.

1183
01:38:02,723 --> 01:38:12,039
[SPEAKER_13]: Well, Sandy, I'm very happy to talk afterwards about what we can do to help your specific case, but I do think that universal...

1184
01:38:12,059 --> 01:38:16,587
[SPEAKER_13]: I know that some people want to scrap universal credit without putting anything in its place.

1185
01:38:16,888 --> 01:38:19,973
[SPEAKER_13]: It has worked in the sense that it has helped many

1186
01:38:19,953 --> 01:38:22,676
[SPEAKER_13]: a couple of hundred thousand people at least into work.

1187
01:38:23,077 --> 01:38:30,765
[SPEAKER_13]: And one of the features of the economy at the moment, whatever the problems we have, is that we have more people in employment than ever before.

1188
01:38:30,825 --> 01:38:33,829
[SPEAKER_13]: We have more women in the workforce than ever before.

1189
01:38:34,069 --> 01:38:39,856
[SPEAKER_13]: And actually incomes are starting to grow faster than any time in the last 12 years.

1190
01:38:40,376 --> 01:38:42,038
[SPEAKER_13]: And that is what we want to focus on.

1191
01:38:42,098 --> 01:38:43,800
[SPEAKER_44]: The man at the back in the grey suit.

1192
01:38:45,468 --> 01:38:59,652
[SPEAKER_15]: Hello Mr Johnson, my name is Dylan, I'm a student at the University of Manchester and I just wanted to ask you, why should a young person between 18 and 25 years old vote for the Conservative Party without using campaign rhetoric?

1193
01:38:59,672 --> 01:39:01,215
[SPEAKER_15]: Just straight answer please.

1194
01:39:01,195 --> 01:39:15,480
[SPEAKER_13]: because I believe that we are the party that is going to do the most to help you to get a fantastic high-wage, high-skilled job... What about all the debt I'm about to graduate with?

1195
01:39:15,961 --> 01:39:24,216
[SPEAKER_13]: And help you to get a home by building record numbers of homes, help you to get onto the housing ladder,

1196
01:39:24,196 --> 01:39:34,296
[SPEAKER_13]: With great respect, sir, we built a record number last year and we have a plan to build a million homes in the next five years.

1197
01:39:34,357 --> 01:39:35,960
[SPEAKER_44]: Hang on, hang on, hang on a minute.

1198
01:39:35,980 --> 01:39:37,763
[SPEAKER_44]: I think there's so much groaning here.

1199
01:39:37,844 --> 01:39:44,938
[SPEAKER_44]: I assume you're thinking of the Conservative pledge to build 200,000 starter homes in 2014 and none of those have been built.

1200
01:39:44,918 --> 01:39:57,365
[SPEAKER_13]: No, well, actually, if you look at what we've done just last year, we built 240,000 homes, which was more than any year in the last 31 years bar one.

1201
01:39:57,886 --> 01:40:01,273
[SPEAKER_13]: And of those, 57,000 were affordable homes.

1202
01:40:01,253 --> 01:40:03,017
[SPEAKER_13]: I don't want to go on my record.

1203
01:40:03,037 --> 01:40:07,687
[SPEAKER_13]: If you look at my record as Mayor of London, we outbuilt Labour by miles when I was Mayor of London.

1204
01:40:07,968 --> 01:40:11,456
[SPEAKER_13]: We will build the homes for young people growing up in this country.

1205
01:40:11,676 --> 01:40:14,262
[SPEAKER_13]: We will also make sure that they have the jobs to go to.

1206
01:40:14,643 --> 01:40:16,748
[SPEAKER_13]: And we will...

1207
01:40:16,968 --> 01:40:19,093
[SPEAKER_13]: I'll answer that.

1208
01:40:19,073 --> 01:40:20,916
[SPEAKER_44]: that's not the second time he's asked it.

