1387
01:53:13,924 --> 01:53:15,025
[SPEAKER_13]: We are going to continue to fund the NHS.

1388
01:53:15,065 --> 01:53:19,951
[SPEAKER_44]: There's so many hands up and we've got so few minutes left, so I'm going to try and have as few hands as I can.

1389
01:53:20,011 --> 01:53:21,553
[SPEAKER_44]: Yes, I'll do about three or four.

1390
01:53:21,533 --> 01:53:22,876
[SPEAKER_44]: If you keep your questions brief.

1391
01:53:22,896 --> 01:53:23,657
[SPEAKER_44]: The man with the glasses.

1392
01:53:24,218 --> 01:53:28,026
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm a physiotherapist, and the problem is across the board in the NHS.

1393
01:53:29,569 --> 01:53:34,719
[SPEAKER_02]: Part of the problem was getting rid of the NHS bursary, which stopped a lot of mature students coming back.

1394
01:53:34,739 --> 01:53:41,453
[SPEAKER_02]: I wouldn't have been able to train without that bursary, and you've shut a lot of people out with that, so would you reverse that decision to help get people back in?

1395
01:53:41,633 --> 01:53:42,535
[SPEAKER_44]: OK, let's take a couple more.

1396
01:53:42,555 --> 01:53:43,677
[SPEAKER_44]: The woman with the glasses here.

1397
01:53:44,281 --> 01:53:47,806
[SPEAKER_38]: I'm a junior doctor in A&E in the NHS.

1398
01:53:48,106 --> 01:53:52,412
[SPEAKER_38]: And over the past nine years since you've been in power, I've seen that waiting lists are getting longer.

1399
01:53:52,913 --> 01:53:55,517
[SPEAKER_38]: People are in trolleys for hours and hours in A&E.

1400
01:53:55,537 --> 01:53:56,759
[SPEAKER_38]: And it's not just inconvenient.

1401
01:53:56,839 --> 01:53:57,640
[SPEAKER_38]: People are dying.

1402
01:53:57,780 --> 01:53:59,082
[SPEAKER_38]: And I think you're lying to us.

1403
01:53:59,262 --> 01:54:02,346
[SPEAKER_38]: Every year, you promise more money for the NHS.

1404
01:54:02,386 --> 01:54:08,475
[SPEAKER_38]: But the reality is, in the NHS, people who work there and who use it know that that money isn't getting through.

1405
01:54:08,795 --> 01:54:14,203
[SPEAKER_38]: Why should we trust that you're going to get this $26 billion for the NHS when you've got years of cuts and people are dying?

1406
01:54:14,538 --> 01:54:16,701
[SPEAKER_38]: One more, the man in the pink shirt.

1407
01:54:20,562 --> 01:54:26,527
[SPEAKER_29]: A big part of the election process is all about the trust that you want us to put into you.

1408
01:54:27,488 --> 01:54:35,155
[SPEAKER_29]: And even in this sort of campaign over the last week, we've seen Twitter handles that have been changed by the Conservatives.

1409
01:54:35,215 --> 01:54:39,519
[SPEAKER_29]: We've seen URLs that have been bought purporting to be from Labour, I think.

1410
01:54:39,539 --> 01:54:47,346
[SPEAKER_29]: And you're asking us to put our trust in big decisions, but yet even simple things, you can't seem to get that right.

1411
01:54:47,386 --> 01:54:49,708
[SPEAKER_29]: So why on earth should we trust you with anything else?

1412
01:54:49,688 --> 01:54:55,416
[SPEAKER_13]: Well, look at what...

1413
01:54:55,436 --> 01:54:55,636
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

1414
01:54:55,656 --> 01:54:57,499
[SPEAKER_13]: Let's get back to this central issue.

1415
01:54:58,079 --> 01:55:02,005
[SPEAKER_13]: Look at what I said I would do when I set out to be Mayor of London ten years ago.

1416
01:55:02,345 --> 01:55:04,949
[SPEAKER_13]: No, in fairness, Mr Johnson, that's not the question.

1417
01:55:04,989 --> 01:55:06,851
[SPEAKER_13]: The question is about the NHS.

1418
01:55:07,011 --> 01:55:08,974
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm having questions about whether I can deliver.

1419
01:55:09,255 --> 01:55:10,396
[SPEAKER_13]: We massively cut crime.

1420
01:55:10,656 --> 01:55:12,098
[SPEAKER_13]: I promised to cut crime and we did.

1421
01:55:12,299 --> 01:55:13,300
[SPEAKER_13]: We had a huge investment

1422
01:55:13,280 --> 01:55:16,024
[SPEAKER_13]: very substantially, a 50% cut in the murder rate.

1423
01:55:16,204 --> 01:55:21,091
[SPEAKER_13]: We massively invested in transport and cut delays on the tube by 30%.

1424
01:55:21,551 --> 01:55:24,075
[SPEAKER_13]: We outbuilt the Labour Party when it came to housing.

1425
01:55:24,155 --> 01:55:25,637
[SPEAKER_13]: I overdelivered on my promises.

1426
01:55:25,657 --> 01:55:35,490
[SPEAKER_13]: When you look at what I promised on the steps of Downing Street a few months ago, three or so months ago, I promised we would put 20,000 more police on the streets of our country.

1427
01:55:35,470 --> 01:55:36,652
[SPEAKER_13]: are coming there.

1428
01:55:36,672 --> 01:55:37,855
[SPEAKER_13]: I have talked to them.

1429
01:55:37,875 --> 01:55:39,498
[SPEAKER_13]: They are being recruited now.

1430
01:55:39,939 --> 01:55:45,369
[SPEAKER_13]: I said we would put the biggest ever cash boost into the NHS and it is happening.

1431
01:55:45,790 --> 01:55:50,379
[SPEAKER_13]: We are doing 20 hospital upgrades and 40 new hospitals.

1432
01:55:50,820 --> 01:55:54,627
[SPEAKER_13]: To get to all the points being raised, yes, of course,

1433
01:55:54,607 --> 01:56:00,554
[SPEAKER_13]: I understand that things have been tough in the NHS, and I understand the pressures that the NHS is under.

1434
01:56:00,574 --> 01:56:05,080
[SPEAKER_13]: But as I say, I've talked to hundreds of doctors and nurses in the last few months.

1435
01:56:05,180 --> 01:56:08,985
[SPEAKER_13]: I know the massive, massive demand that the NHS faces.

1436
01:56:09,205 --> 01:56:15,633
[SPEAKER_13]: But we can only meet that demand if we have a dynamic economy.

1437
01:56:15,974 --> 01:56:19,618
[SPEAKER_13]: And I'm afraid we won't get this economy really moving again

1438
01:56:19,598 --> 01:56:24,143
[SPEAKER_13]: We won't get the investment coming in, and you know what I'm going to say, until we get...

1439
01:56:24,203 --> 01:56:24,603
[SPEAKER_13]: It's true.

1440
01:56:24,964 --> 01:56:25,744
[SPEAKER_13]: It happens to be true.

1441
01:56:25,764 --> 01:56:26,986
[SPEAKER_13]: Until we get Brexit done.

1442
01:56:27,406 --> 01:56:29,348
[SPEAKER_13]: And at the moment, that is hanging over us.

1443
01:56:29,468 --> 01:56:31,210
[SPEAKER_13]: It's paralysing Parliament.

1444
01:56:31,590 --> 01:56:39,539
[SPEAKER_13]: And to get back to your trust point, that is, in my view, the single biggest corrosion of trust in politics.

1445
01:56:39,659 --> 01:56:45,825
[SPEAKER_13]: People voted three and a half years ago for their will to be respected.

1446
01:56:45,805 --> 01:56:54,078
[SPEAKER_13]: Every other party that you've had on tonight is basically trying to frustrate that outcome.

1447
01:56:54,359 --> 01:56:56,422
[SPEAKER_13]: We have a deal, and it's a good deal.

1448
01:56:57,063 --> 01:56:58,165
[SPEAKER_13]: It will allow us...

1449
01:56:58,365 --> 01:56:59,187
[SPEAKER_13]: It's a great deal.

1450
01:56:59,587 --> 01:57:00,068
[SPEAKER_13]: It's there.

1451
01:57:00,168 --> 01:57:00,950
[SPEAKER_13]: It's ready to go.

1452
01:57:01,010 --> 01:57:03,554
[SPEAKER_13]: It's, as I never tire of saying, oven ready.

1453
01:57:04,035 --> 01:57:04,996
[SPEAKER_13]: OK, we're out of time.

1454
01:57:05,036 --> 01:57:06,158
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm so sorry.

1455
01:57:06,338 --> 01:57:10,345
[SPEAKER_13]: And it will enable us to have 2020

1456
01:57:10,325 --> 01:57:17,275
[SPEAKER_13]: not as a year of two pointless referendums, but 2020 as a year of prosperity and growth.

1457
01:57:17,315 --> 01:57:19,579
[SPEAKER_13]: That's what I want to see.

1458
01:57:19,599 --> 01:57:20,941
[SPEAKER_44]: Mr Johnson, thank you very much.

1459
01:57:26,489 --> 01:57:29,734
[SPEAKER_44]: So, thank you very much to Boris Johnson.

1460
01:57:36,498 --> 01:57:39,663
[SPEAKER_44]: And that concludes our evening.

1461
01:57:39,683 --> 01:57:41,006
[SPEAKER_44]: It's been worth it, hasn't it, I think?

1462
01:57:41,446 --> 01:57:46,515
[SPEAKER_44]: So you can, of course, carry on the debate by tuning in to live analysis opinion from The Spinner on the news channel.

1463
01:57:47,096 --> 01:57:57,493
[SPEAKER_44]: But from us, from our audience, from all our party leaders, thank you very much for watching.

